{META_DATA}: INTO THE WILD
{META_DATA}: Written by
{META_DATA}: Sean Penn
{META_DATA}: Based on the book by
{META_DATA}: Jon Krakauer
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 1 EXT. THE STAMPEDE TRAIL - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SUPER:
{DIALOGUE}: Tuesday, April 28th 1992
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDE-SHOT: A vast, snow-blanketed wilderness that sits beneath the icy summits of the highest mountain range in North America.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is BIG Alaska.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A beat up 4x4 pick-up enters very small into the upper left corner of frame on an unkept, snow-packed road, and comes to a stop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A figure exits the passenger side and moves around the front of the truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can just make out the rifle sticking out of his backpack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR a very distant "Thank You" as the figure walks away from the road and away from the truck, seemingly into nowhere.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{DIALOGUE}: Hey!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The figure with backpack and rifle, henceforth BACKPACK, stopping in his tracks, turns around in the direction of the truck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Come here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACKPACK walks back to the truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he approaches the driver's door, we
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CUT IN TO: TIGHT SHOT over the back-packed shoulder onto the DRIVER.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (referring to items we see sitting on dashboard)
{DIALOGUE}: You left your watch, your comb, your change...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We STAY on the DRIVER as BACKPACK speaks:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BACKPACK
{DIALOGUE}: Keep it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want your money.
{DIALOGUE}: And I already have a watch.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BACKPACK
{DIALOGUE}: If you don't take it, I'm gonna throw it away.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to know what time it is, what day it is, or where I am.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BACKPACK (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want to see anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: None of that matters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The driver reaches behind the seat of the truck, pulls out an old pair of rubber work boots.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{META_DATA}: (handing him the boots)
{DIALOGUE}: Take em.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a pause as Backpack considers accepting the boots.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: If you make it out alive, give me a call, and I'll tell you how to get the boots back to me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can feel over Backpack's shoulder that he has taken the boots and is putting them on but we STAY on the driver.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BACKPACK
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, do me a favor, will ya?
{DIALOGUE}: Take a picture of me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Backpack hands him an Instamatic camera and starts walking backwards.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PULL BACK with him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And he maintains his back to us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When he stops, we CONTINUE until he is FULL-FRAME, head-to-toe from behind, posing.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CU: driver
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLICK.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He snaps the shot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Backpack re-enters frame in an OVER-SHOULDER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Driver hands him the camera.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{DIALOGUE}: You gonna be alright?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BACKPACK
{DIALOGUE}: I'll be better than that.
{META_DATA}: (I'll be who I am.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Backpack exits the frame, we SLOWLY ZOOM past the concerned face of the driver onto the loose change, the comb, and the watch on the dash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Throughout the ZOOM, the SOUND of FOOTSTEPS CRUNCHING THE SNOW, FADE into the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ORIGINAL WIDE-SHOT:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see the small form of the truck and the smaller form of the Backpacker walking away from the truck until the Backpacker has exited the frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The truck takes a BEAT, turns around in the snow, and accelerates back into the direction from which it came.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the truck exits frame, we -
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 2 EXT. COMMENCEMENT GROUNDS, EMORY UNIVERSITY, ATLANTA - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SUPER:
{DIALOGUE}: May 1990
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The crowd of family and friends, and of course, students.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Assembled on fold-out chairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The broad lawn.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INTERCUT: CHRIS MCCANDLESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We don't see his face, just feet pounding the pavement at an increasing pace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One by one the names of graduates announced.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their bright young faces, capped heads, and gowns, glide up to the podium to accept their diplomas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INTERCUT: Chris, on his run, sweatshirt hood over head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Amongst assembled crowd and family we find: THE MCCANDLESS': BILLIE, mid to late forties with dark striking eyes; WALT, a taciturn man, early fifties; and CARINE, eighteen, pretty with her mother's eyes and waist length brown hair, a gold crucifix dangles from her neck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They look around, looking for Chris, he's nowhere in sight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: INTERCUT: Chris, in a shower (PHOTO-SONICS) He TURNS INTO CAMERA, the water streaming down his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: From the announcement podium comes the name of their son and brother, CHRISTOPHER JOHNSON MCCANDLESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The McCandless family increasingly panicked over Chris' absence, when almost magically, he appears in full cap and gown.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 4.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Disregarding the steps that lead up to the podium platform, the small-framed but athletic CHRIS MCCANDLESS leaps jubilantly onto the stage in a single bound, frightening Billie, a little wince from Walt, and Carine "That's our Chris."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And just as quickly as Chris has been handed his diploma, he civilly descends the platform steps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLO-MO: A ballet of graduation caps float upward into a frame of blue sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR Chris' voice OVER this image as we intermittently cut away from the caps against the sky to focus on his parents.
{META_DATA}: (HIGH ANGLE: floating caps in FOREGROUND, Walt and Billie delight upon the caps.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An outer glee in sharp contrast to voice over:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I see them standing at the formal gates of their colleges, I see my father strolling out under the ochre sandstone arch, the red tiles glinting like bent plates of blood behind his head, I see my mother with a few light books at her hip standing at the pillar made of tiny bricks with the wrought-iron gate still open behind her, its sword-tips black in the May air, they are about to graduate, they are about to get married, they are kids, they are dumb, all they know is they are innocent, they would never hurt anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to go up to them and say Stop, don't do it--she's the wrong woman, he's the wrong man, you are going to do things you cannot imagine you would ever do, you are going to do bad things to children, you are going to suffer in ways you never heard of, you are going to want to die.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to go up to them there in the late May sunlight and say it, her hungry pretty blank face turning to me,
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 5.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: her pitiful beautiful untouched body, his arrogant handsome blind face turning to me, his pitiful beautiful untouched body, but I don't do it.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to live.
{DIALOGUE}: I take them up like the male and female paper dolls and bang them together at the hips like chips of flint as if to strike sparks from them, I say...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The last graduation cap falls out of the `blue sky' frame, and into...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 3 INT. ATLANTA RESTAURANT - LATER
{META_DATA}: (Graduation ceremony wardrobe)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt and Billie sit at a table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A Cadillac can be seen through the window (ATLANTA LANDMARK), parked beside the restaurant.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Here they are.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt looks out the window and sees Chris drive up in his old yellow Datsun with Carine in the passenger seat beside him, and pulls up to the space beside the Cadillac.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 4 INT. DATSUN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is holding a book from which he reads aloud the LAST LINE OF THE POEM...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I say...Do what you are going to do, and I will tell about it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Who wrote that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it could've been either one of us, couldn't it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He hands a book of Sharon Olds' poetry to her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: There's a lot of great poems in there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 6.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks, big brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They exit the car and frame.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 5 INT. ATLANTA RESTAURANT - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris and Carine join Walt and Billie at the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Billie gets up and gives Chris a big hug.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: You scared the daylights out of me, jumping on to that stage, oh my god.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris gives Carine a look.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt extends his hand to Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: Congratulations, son.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They all sit and pick up menus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm starving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 6 INT. ATLANTA RESTAURANT - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The foods on the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is devouring a steak.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: My grades are gonna be good enough, I think, to get into Harvard Law.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: That's a big deal.
{DIALOGUE}: What do you have left in your college fund?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: It's an inheritance, dad.
{DIALOGUE}: I've only been spending it as a college fund...Exactly twenty-four thousand five hundred dollars and sixty-eight cents.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: That's very specific.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I had to go to the bank this morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 7.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we'll certainly contribute the balance for Harvard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: I've got to figure out what I'm going to do.
{DIALOGUE}: I got a lot of things to pack and organize here first.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm so glad you're getting out of that place you're living.
{DIALOGUE}: It was so much nicer when you lived on campus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: You'll come to Annandale before you disappear on us, won't you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (reluctantly)
{DIALOGUE}: Sure, I will.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine's not so sure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: You promise?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (whining)
{DIALOGUE}: Mom.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, your father and I want to make a present to you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: We want to get you out of that junker.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: What's a junker?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt points outside to the Datsun.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: The Datsun?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: We want to get you a new car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (appalled)
{DIALOGUE}: A new car?
{DIALOGUE}: Why the hell would I want a new car?
{DIALOGUE}: The Datsun runs great.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 8.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (Mocking the Cadillac)
{DIALOGUE}: Do you think I want some fancy boat?
{DIALOGUE}: Or are you worried about what the neighbors might think?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: We weren't going to get you a Cadillac, Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: Just a nice new car that's safe to drive.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't know when that thing's just going to suddenly blow up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Blow up?
{DIALOGUE}: Blow up?!
{DIALOGUE}: Are you guys crazy?
{DIALOGUE}: It's a great car.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't need a new car.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want a new car.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't want anything.
{DIALOGUE}: Thing, thing, thing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Under the table, Carine jabs Chris' leg.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris returning to polite -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But, thanks anyway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: Everything's gotta be difficult.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I said thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: I just don't want anything.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The group returns to some superficial calm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: I wouldn't say no to a new car.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (mumbling a rib)
{DIALOGUE}: Ivana Trump McCandless.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{META_DATA}: (laughing it off)
{DIALOGUE}: Shut up, Chris.
{META_DATA}: (to her parents, seriously)
{DIALOGUE}: Seriously, I'll pay you back.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 7 INT. OFF-CAMPUS ROOMING HOUSE, SECOND-FLOOR, ATLANTA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OVER Chris' shoulder, he frisbees his graduation cap from the upstairs window to his parents parting Cadillac on the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 9.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they wave goodbye, Carine catches the cap from the backseat window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with a parting smile to her brother, she poses with it on her own head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris smiles and waves goodbye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the Cadillac drifts away, his smile disappears into something other than sadness.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 8 INT. OFF-CAMPUS ROOMING HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a warm ambient light, we SEE a black and white poster on a barren wall: Poncho-clad Clint Eastwood from "The Good, The Bad, And The Ugly."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We TILT DOWN a stack of books sitting on the floor - Tolstoy, Stegner, Thoreau, Jack London, and Pasternak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beside them, a camper's backpack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits in introspection at his desk by candlelight.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The room is spare, supporting his monkish lifestyle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But on the desk before him, he counts out $500.68 from a bank envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pockets those bills and change, then removes a check for $24,000 made out to OXFAM America from the same bank envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He scribbles a note: These are all my savings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Feed someone with it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Signed, Chris McCandless.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He then slides the note and the check into a pre-addressed Oxford Famine Relief Fund (in Boston) envelope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls his wallet from his back pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pulls all the cards and pictures from its sleeves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Considering each, he flicks them into a trash bin, one by one.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Finally coming to his social security card, he holds it to the candles flame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the flame burns bright we -
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 9 EXT. ATLANTA HIGHWAY - SUNRISE'
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MUSIC (Gordon Peterson's BIG HARD SUN or as radio source Tom Petty's FREE FALLING) rises and PRESENTATION TITLES OVER:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A 1982 DATSUN B210 emerges from the rising sun as the car heads west out of Atlanta.
{META_DATA}: (HIGHWAY 20 TO 78 TO 40)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PRESENTATION TITLES and MUSIC carry OVER:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 9A.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MONTAGE: We travel with Chris and his Datsun through the towns and open highways, landscapes and landmarks, days and nights, that lead to the Mojave desert in the West.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 10.
{META_DATA}: (In contrast to his introspection of the previous night, Chris is buoyant throughout this sequence.)
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 10 EXT. DESERT, SOMEWHERE BETWEEN KINGMAN, ARIZONA AND LAS VEGAS, NEVADA - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: (CRANE SHOT) We see Chris stop the Datsun in the middle of the desert road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We (CRANE?)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DOWN to a close-up through the windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris looks left.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then, right.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Into the rearview mirror, and suddenly turns the wheel, veering the Datsun off the paved highway into the vast desert.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we CRANE back UP, the Datsun moves into the horizon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: END PRESENTATION TITLES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FADE MUSIC
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 11 EXT. DETRITAL WASH - TWILIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: WEST-FACING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Datsun sits in the magical pastel twilight just before darkness slides over the desert.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It is positioned at the foot of a wash wall that edges the soup bowl.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: EAST-FACING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Datsun, a yellow speck in the frame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Coyotes yap at the moon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Other than that, no sound on the desert floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance, voluptuous cumulonimbus clouds boil upward catching the last rosy glow of the west-setting sun over the rim of the upper Detrital watershed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see strobe bursts of lightning followed by muffled thunder illuminating the thunder clouds from within.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Short SERIES OF ANGLES as we MOVE IN on the distant gullies and ravines, starting to run with copious amounts of water.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 12 INT. DATSUN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris McCandless, in the same clothes he had been in back in the rooming house, sleeps in the back seat of the Datsun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His head supported by his backpack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We begin to HEAR a rumble.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But this rumble is not thunder.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It rapidly builds into an alarming ROAR.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The roar grows to a deafening level.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris awakens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 11.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he peeks up from the backseat looking forward through the windshield, he just barely catches sight of the leading edge of a flash flood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A four-foot high wall of water, mud and debris makes impact with the Datsun, momentarily enveloping it in water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly the car is SLAMMED against the cliff.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CRACK!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits upright, disoriented.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: POV: As far as the eye can see in the desert moonlight, water has taken over the desert with a flash flood.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: However, there's no panic in Chris' face as we observe him past a new crack in the wet windshield.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The water, while violent seems to have topped off just above the wheels.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris gets a slight smile on his face, as the car settles into its new position below the cliff.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He returns to sleep.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 13 EXT. DESERT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: What remains of Chris' travelling money burns in a pile beside the Datsun on the sun-lit but muddy desert floor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow a very long set of footprints (CAMERA TRACKING/TRUE VERTICAL) away from the burning cash through the mud, finally tilting up to the footprint maker, Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Slogging toward high ground.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDE-SHOT: We see the abandoned Datsun nearly a mile behind Chris as he walks toward us wearing his backpack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes very close to camera (only a day or two's stubble on his face) and as we PAN him 180, we see as much wilderness before us as we did behind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: REPRISE MUSIC OVER MAIN TITLE:
{META_DATA}: (INTO THE WILD)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris walks into the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COMPLETE AND END MAIN TITLES.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 14 INT. COLLEGE BUILDING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SHAKY HAND-HELD HOME VIDEO IMAGE (4 YEARS EARLIER):
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 12.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris McCandless speaking to camera holds a microphone in a shadowy room, doing his Geraldo Rivera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's tongue-in- cheek at best.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: This is Emory University freshman Chris McCandless reporting from the vault at Thompson Hall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He indicates a hatchway in the floor leading to a brightly lit corridor below.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: We have just dynamited the hatchway and are the first human beings to step foot into this vault in over a hundred years.
{DIALOGUE}: Somewhere in here lies the secret of the great beast within us all.
{DIALOGUE}: A beast built on lies, corruption, and greed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR a GROWLING SOUND from behind Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: And there it is!
{DIALOGUE}: The legendary beast Mocra.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA quickly PANS to a blanket-wrapped, crawling FELLOW STUDENT in a grotesque Halloween mask.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We MOVE INTO CU on the monster growling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: QUICK PAN back to Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (in mock fright)
{DIALOGUE}: We've got to get out of here quick and re- secure the hatch while we make a plan of how to kill the beast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA SHAKES all over like a bad horror film trying to stay with Chris as he makes a quick escape down the hatchway into the University dorm corridor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CLUMSY VIDEO TIME CUT: Chris nailing the last nail in the hatchway from below.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He climbs down the steps where he exchanges his hammer for his microphone from an off- camera source.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, it looks like we've succeeded -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR the monster's GROWL from above.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 13.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: - at least for the moment, in sealing the beast back into the vault.
{DIALOGUE}: Your humble reporter, Chris McCandless will now struggle with the journalistic question of ethics: Will he retain his reporter's objectiveness or save the future of human truth by slaying this awful beast?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives us a look of vaudevillian puzzlement - what will he do?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CONTINUE VIDEO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We pick up with Chris in a corridor outside a door with a cheap paper-and-tape label announcing the adjacent room as the office of Ted Turner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Once again, your humble reporter Chris McCandless.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR OS students commenting on Chris and his video crew:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OS STUDENT
{DIALOGUE}: What is this?
{DIALOGUE}: Filmmaking 101?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OS STUDENT #2
{DIALOGUE}: Point the camera at me.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a star.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris speaking straight to camera, still tongue-in-cheek:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (with a Wizard of Oz tone)
{DIALOGUE}: Pay no attention to the voices behind the curtain.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 15 INT. WOULD-BE TED TURNER OFFICE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A FELLOW STUDENT PLAYING TED TURNER with obvious fake mustache is locked into an episode of Matlock on his television set as our bold reporter, Chris, barges in.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Ted!
{DIALOGUE}: We've got a monster in the vault.
{DIALOGUE}: It represents all the corruption, the deceit, and greed within us all.
{DIALOGUE}: I must slay it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 14.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TED TURNER/STUDENT
{META_DATA}: (worst acting we've ever seen)
{DIALOGUE}: McCandless, how many times have I had to tell you?
{DIALOGUE}: I've had to tell you that you are a journalist and you can't get personally involved in your cases...or your stories.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Ted!
{DIALOGUE}: I know how to kill it.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'm the only one who knows.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't keep sending me on stories and expecting me to do nothing!
{DIALOGUE}: I look like some kind of an idiot.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TED TURNER/STUDENT
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know who you're talking to?
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Ted Turner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Behind Chris in the corridor outside Ted's office, a PANICKED STUDENT arrives at the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PANICKED STUDENT
{DIALOGUE}: McCandless!
{DIALOGUE}: You've got to hurry!
{DIALOGUE}: The monster is scratching at the hatchway.
{DIALOGUE}: He'll be out in no time.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TED TURNER/STUDENT
{META_DATA}: (threatening)
{DIALOGUE}: It'll mean your job, Chris McCandless.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (to Ted)
{DIALOGUE}: That's it, Ted.
{DIALOGUE}: Fire me if you want but this beast must be slayed.
{DIALOGUE}: Microphone in hand, Chris makes haste.
{DIALOGUE}: The CAMERA RUNS WITH HIM out the door, through the corridor, up a set of steps to the hatchway.
{DIALOGUE}: As he arrives, the monster appears above him in the hatchway crawl space having pulled off the board Chris had nailed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (into camera)
{DIALOGUE}: This is the only thing that can kill the monster.
{DIALOGUE}: It's gonna be risky but without great risk, there is no freedom.
{DIALOGUE}: So we will now hear from the famous singer - Chris McCandless.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 15.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A piano is PUSHED INTO FRAME beside Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A YOUNG BLACK STUDENT pulls a stool in front of the piano and begins to play.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris begins to serenade the monster, intermittently sharing the serenade directly into camera as well.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He bursts into an uninhibited solo of Tender Is The Night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA TILTS UP to the monster looking out the hatchway, slowly dying from the song being sung.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the song continues to be sung and the monster continues to die, the AUDIO RECEDES and VIDEO IMAGES GO TO SLO MO.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When we were little, Chris was very to himself.
{DIALOGUE}: He wasn't anti-social, he always had friends, and everybody liked him - but he could go off and entertain himself for hours, he didn't seem to need toys or friends.
{DIALOGUE}: He could be alone without being lonely.
{DIALOGUE}: The secrets our parents kept, though unknown to Chris and I, led to bouts of rage and even violence between them that we had been forced to witness since we were very young.
{DIALOGUE}: It seemed like they never fought without us.
{DIALOGUE}: I remember the first family meeting to let Chris and me in on their plans for getting a divorce.
{DIALOGUE}: They wanted us to choose which of them we'd live with.
{DIALOGUE}: I cried my eyes out.
{DIALOGUE}: But the divorce never happened, though the threats and meetings never stopped.
{DIALOGUE}: It wasn't long before Chris and I shut off -- we would tell mom and dad to go ahead and get the divorce.
{DIALOGUE}: Chris and I just wanted to get away from their fights and mom kept promising to get out and take us with her as soon as their company made enough money.
{DIALOGUE}: Dad had been the young genius [that] NASA enlisted to do [crucial] designs for the American satellite radar systems that would be our answer to the Russian Sputnik.
{DIALOGUE}: And mom and he later started up a consulting firm combining her get-up- and-go resourcefulness with his wealth of knowledge.
{DIALOGUE}: By the time the company actually made its first million, the careerism and money seemed to erase her memory of the promise she'd made us.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 16.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I think this is when Chris began to see "careers" as a diseased invention of the twentieth century and to resent money and the useless priority people made of it in their lives.
{DIALOGUE}: He'd begun planning to "slay the beast"...to make himself free.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VIDEO IMAGE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The beast dies.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CHAPTER 1: BIRTH - FADE IN:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 16 INT. TENT (IN THE SCRUB BRUSH BESIDE LAKE MEAD) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a pile of berries sitting atop a handkerchief.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beside them, a survivalist's guide to edible growth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: POV: THE TOP OF THE TENT - SOFT FOCUS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The glare of the sun penetrating the canvas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A fly buzzes and lands, hanging upside down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The image is blurry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ECU: CHRIS' EYES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Delirious in the heat, we WIDEN OUT to see that he's filthy (2 weeks of growth on his face and naked.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He makes his way out of the tent, peers at the relentless sun and scurries to his backpack where he removes a canteen, barely a sip of water left in it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He downs it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 17 EXT. LAKE MEAD DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The following short vignettes are silent and focused exclusively on Chris:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 1.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Recreational BOATERS on Lake Mead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GIRLS in bikinis.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BOYS on boats eating Kentucky Fried Chicken.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At lake-side, an unusual sight - the NEW Chris McCandless, a sun and dirt-beaten bum with a backpack.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 17.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A family ski-boat has taken Chris on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They give him water, dropping him at the north end of the lake at TEMPLE BAR MARINA.
{META_DATA}: (Director's Note: HIGH ANGLE, TIGHT, sees Chris and the glimmering water treadmilling below)
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 4.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris washes himself in the lake by the marina.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18 ESTABLISHING SHOT: CAFE, TEMPLE BAR MARINA
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 19 INT. MARINA CAFE, UNISEX RESTROOM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris brushes his teeth.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I need a name.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He takes a swallow of water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rinses his mouth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Spits it out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then checks his bearded face in the mirror.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He likes what he sees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he wipes the corners of his mouth with a tissue and throws it into the bin below the sink, he notices a discarded tube of lipstick.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He picks it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's down to its end.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Yet with what lipstick remains, he writes on the mirror:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ALEXANDER SUPERTRAMP WAS HERE JULY 1990
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 20 EXT. MARINA CAFE (BLDG REAR) - SUNDOWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is behind the cafe beside a pair of dumpsters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He removes the Datsun's license plates from his backpack and discards them deeply into the garbage.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 17A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 21 EXT. MARINA CAFE (BLDG FRONT) - SUNDOWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris appears from behind the cafe lugging his backpack up the rise from the cafe to the highway and starts thumbing for a ride.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 18.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 22 INT. MCCANDLESS HOME, ANNANDALE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS shots to accompany V.O.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Toward the end of June, Chris had mailed our parents his final grade report.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt and Billie open the envelope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Almost all A's.
{DIALOGUE}: "A" in Apartheid in South African Society and History of Anthropological Thought; A- in Contemporary African Politics and the Food Crisis in Africa; and on it went.
{DIALOGUE}: Clever boy, my brother.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We observe Carine in a delicate afternoon light.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is sitting up on her bed with an unread book, looking out the window toward us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But by the end of July we hadn't heard anything from him and my parents were getting very worried.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine's POV: Walt with his arm around Billie in the yard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Chris had never had a phone, so they decided to drive down to Atlanta and surprise him.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 22A EXT. ROAD TO TAHOE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, backpack on, walking away from camera.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 23 EXT. HIGHWAY - ATLANTA - DAY (END JULY 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Walt and Billie's car pass under an Atlanta mileage sign.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 19.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When they arrived at the apartment, there was a "For Rent" sign in his window, and the manager told my parents that Chris had moved out at the end of June.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 24 EXT. OFF-CAMPUS ROOMING HOUSE, ATLANTA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We observe Walt and Billie chatting with Chris' apartment manager.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When they got home, I had to hand them all the letters they had sent Chris that summer which had been returned in a bundle.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 25 INT. MCCANDLESS HOME, ANNANDALE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bundle of letters are splayed out on the kitchen table - "Return to Sender" stamps visible.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Chris had instructed the post office to hold them until August 1st so that mom and dad wouldn't know that anything was up.
{DIALOGUE}: Some part of me understood what he had done.
{DIALOGUE}: That he had spent the previous four years fulfilling an absurd and onerous duty in graduating from college.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We return to the image of Carine sitting on her bed as she plops on Chris' old graduation cap.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We slowly ZOOM IN on her throughout the remaining V.O.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: And now, at last he was unincumbered.
{DIALOGUE}: Emancipated from the stifling world of parents and peers.
{DIALOGUE}: Abstraction, security, and material excess.
{DIALOGUE}: Those things that cut Chris off from the raw truth of his existence.
{DIALOGUE}: I only hoped he was safe...and I missed him.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 26 EXT. SIERRA NEVADA MOUNTAINS (LAKE TAHOE AREA) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 20.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HELICOPTER SHOT: (MUSIC OVER: PHILIP GLASS) WE FIND CHRIS MAKING HIS STRIDES THROUGH PINES AND PEAKS, IN AWE OF THE SCALE AND POWER OF THIS LANDSCAPE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TRACKING SHOT (GROUND LEVEL): CLOSE ON Chris, surrounded by a summit grove embraced in its nature.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: A DEER drinking from a creek, pops its head up between trees and scrub, watching the alien human pass.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An EAGLE soars above (perhaps it was this POV represented in our helicopter shot)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WATER babbling in a mountain creek.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VARIOUS WILDLIFE SHOTS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Chris - In his eyes we see the landscape inject itself.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 27 EXT. CAMPSITE, PACIFIC CREST TRAIL - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SEQUENCE: Chris makes camp beside a stream pulling a sack of rice from his backpack and cooking it.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 28 EXT. CAMPSITE, PACIFIC CREST TRAIL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wrapped in his own "The Good, The Bad, And The Ugly" poncho, Chris eats rice while crouched beside a campfire reading from Jack London's White Fang.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 29 EXT. PACIFIC CREST TRAIL - FURTHER NORTH - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is on the move north through the gorgeous landscape of the Sierras, humming as he walks, when he comes upon a sign on the trail: PERMIT CAMPING IN DESIGNATED CAMPGROUNDS ONLY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris bows to the sign as one would to speak to a small child.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (singing)
{DIALOGUE}: Sign, sign.
{DIALOGUE}: Everywhere a sign.
{DIALOGUE}: Fuckin' up the scenery, breakin' my mind.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 21.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Do this.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't do that.
{DIALOGUE}: Can't you read the sign?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And then, very impulsively, he karate kicks the sign off its post into a log collapsing into ---
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 30 OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 31 EXT. CAMPSITE II, PACIFIC CREST TRAIL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A burning log collapses in Chris' campfire, reduced to glowing embers.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 32 INT. TENT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is awakened by the SOUND of TWIGS SNAPPING in a nearby thicket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He quickly grabs a knife from his backpack, unzips six inches of the tent door open.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see his eyes peering out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The CRACKLING moves closer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His grip on the knife tightens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly a hot white light hits his face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And a VOICE comes from behind the light.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: U.S. Forestry.
{DIALOGUE}: Could you step out of the tent please?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now we see the FOREST RANGER appear from the thicket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris exits the tent, catching himself holding the knife.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (as he drops the knife to the ground)
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you were a bear.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{META_DATA}: (approaching)
{DIALOGUE}: I don't blame you.
{DIALOGUE}: You're less than a hundred yards from the nearest den.
{DIALOGUE}: That's why I came over here to talk to you.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have some identification?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 22.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: My name's Alex. I've been travelling a lot and I got robbed and my identification was taken.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: You mind if I take a look in your tent?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Go ahead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Forest Ranger bends over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pops his flashlight through the tent door and peers around a bit before re- addressing Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: You're not the character who knocked down our sign, are ya?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (giggles)
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: Because there was a sign indicating that camping was allowed by permit only.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I don't have a permit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: No, I'm sure you don't.
{DIALOGUE}: Listen, it looks like you've got your food secured pretty good, so I'm not gonna make you move on tonight.
{DIALOGUE}: But, these bears out here are nursing young and you know how that goes.
{DIALOGUE}: Next time, stop at the Rangers station and get yourself a permit.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alright.
{DIALOGUE}: I appreciate it.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna be headed towards the coast tomorrow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FOREST RANGER
{DIALOGUE}: Be careful.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They shake hands and the Forest Ranger disappears into the thicket.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 23.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 33 EXT. THE NORTHERN CREST - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris descends the mountains where they meet the Redwoods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Every perilous step creates a mini landslide down the hill; dirt and gravel.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stops briefly to observe an over-flying commercial airliner.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: (mocking imaginary conversation among passengers) Is that a man mommy?
{DIALOGUE}: That's no mere man, sweetheart.
{DIALOGUE}: That's Alexander SuperTramp!
{DIALOGUE}: King of the wild frontier!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris briefly waves to the airplane above and continues his descent.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 34 OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 35 EXT. HIGHWAY NEAR WILLOW CREEK (AUGUST 10, 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A car slows to a stop.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 36 INT./EXT. CAR-HIGHWAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DRIVER
{DIALOGUE}: This is where I turn off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alright man.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks a lot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is dropped off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The driver veers off the highway and into the distance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is left behind to hitch another ride.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 36A EXT. HIGHWAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA is across the road from Chris as one by one cars pass him by.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He turns to move north by foot and we track with him, his back to oncoming traffic, he continues to hitchhike with an extended thumb.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Something catches his eye in the treeline beside the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 24.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: REVERSE: Chris, moving to the mysterious object.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he lifts it, we see that it is a goofy looking straw hat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He dusts it off, and snugs it onto his head, when a police car comes into frame and stops beside Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With a quick blast of the siren, Chris turns to regard the police car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The POLICEMAN gets out of the car and moves to Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: How're you doin' this evening?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (reluctantly)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm alright.
{DIALOGUE}: What's the matter?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: You wanna put your backpack down on the hood of my car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris does not oblige.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Why?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Because I asked you to, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: But I haven't done anything wrong.
{DIALOGUE}: These are my personal items.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Do you know that it's unlawful to hitchhike on this stretch of highway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You're kidding.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: Do you see a safe area for a vehicle to stop?
{DIALOGUE}: We got a tree-lined highway without a substantial shoulder here.
{DIALOGUE}: And we've had a lot of accidents on this road from people stopping in the traffic lane for hitchhikers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alright, but...I mean, you stopped your car.
{DIALOGUE}: You're in the traffic lane.
{DIALOGUE}: And you can see, there's hardly any cars out here.
{DIALOGUE}: Plus, it's a straight road; you can see for a long ways.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 25.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (in disbelief)
{DIALOGUE}: There's really been accidents along here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: May I see some identification?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now Chris is worried.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I don't have any.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have any identification?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris shakes his head "No."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: POLICEMAN (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (pulling out a ticket)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'm gonna site you for unlawful hitchhiking.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have to appear.
{DIALOGUE}: You can send a check directly to the Humboldt County Clerks Office for restitution.
{DIALOGUE}: If you don't pay it within 30 days, you're subject to fine and warrant.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna trust that you're gonna give me accurate information.
{DIALOGUE}: What's your name?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris can't bring himself to lie.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (a beat)
{DIALOGUE}: McCandless.
{DIALOGUE}: Christopher Johnson McCandless.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 37 INT. MCCANDLESS HOME, ANNANDALE (MID-AUGUST 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt, Billie, and Carine sit around the kitchen table in August.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A copy of Chris' ticket has been sent to the Annandale address and sits before them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Billie and Carine sit silently.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt's on the phone.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: If Chris were trying to disappear, it would have been a pretty uncharacteristic lapse for him to give the police his real place of residence.
{DIALOGUE}: Though my parents had already contacted the Annandale police with their initial concerns, this ticket arriving from California made them frantic.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 26.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: My father called one of his old government friends who put him in touch with a private investigator, someone who'd done work with the DIA and the CIA.
{DIALOGUE}: Using the Willow Creek ticket as a starting point, the investigator began chasing down leads.
{DIALOGUE}: Most of them led far afield -- to Europe and South Africa.
{DIALOGUE}: Ultimately turning up nothing.
{DIALOGUE}: What my dad couldn't believe was that he'd given up his car.
{DIALOGUE}: He seemed to love that Datsun so much.
{DIALOGUE}: It sounded just like Chris to me, though.
{DIALOGUE}: He was very much of the school that you should own nothing except what you could carry on your back at a dead run.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 38 EXT. NORTHERN CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY, NEAR ORICK, 60 MILES SOUTH OF THE OREGON LINE - DAY (MID-AUGUST 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With his backpack lunging and a free hand holding his goofy new hat onto his head, we find Chris at a "dead run" to catch a ride that had overshot him.
{META_DATA}: (Director's note: Don't leave this image too soon.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An old van idles waiting for him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he gets to the passenger side, the woman passenger gets out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is JAN BURRES, early 40's, looks to be still on the long road home from Woodstock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little heavyset, dark wavy hair with a lot of premature grey in it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan moving to the side door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: We just barely saw you there, under that crazy hat of yours.
{DIALOGUE}: We couldn't back up - the van's reverse is broken.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (as Jan fiddles with side door handle)
{DIALOGUE}: Oh.
{DIALOGUE}: That's okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks for stopping.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: This door's a little tricky, I'll get it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with a little pulling, it opens.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Indicating the pony- tailed and bearded driver (RAINEY), early 50's, definitely Woodstock...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Hop in, that's Rainey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 27.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, I'm Rainey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: And I'm Jan.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Rainey.
{DIALOGUE}: Hi Jan.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Alex.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: Alex of the hat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (closing the side door)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan jumps back in passenger seat and the van rolls on.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 39 INT. RAINEY & JAN VAN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3-SHOT - CHRIS BETWEEN THEM IN THE BACKSEAT.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: Were you out there a long time hitching?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Couple of days.
{DIALOGUE}: But sometimes I forget to put my thumb out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Probably, the rest of the time, that hat scares `em away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris checks himself in the rearview mirror and gets a kick out of what he sees (That hat's staying on.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan is looking at the rearview mirror too, observing Chris with mild concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: When's the last time you ate something?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pulls out a bag of berries and edible plants he's collected.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (excited)
{DIALOGUE}: See that?
{DIALOGUE}: I've got this book and it shows you all the plants and berries that are edible.
{DIALOGUE}: You can find things wherever you go.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan steals a glance to Rainey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's hip.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 28.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: We were just in town getting some beads and stuff.
{DIALOGUE}: Jan does handicrafts, so we're usually going from one swap meet to another.
{DIALOGUE}: She's so good at what she does, we sold everything.
{DIALOGUE}: So, we set up camp at Orick Beach.
{DIALOGUE}: You're welcome to camp there with us.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: And eat there with us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is beaming at the thought of real food.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 40 EXT. CAMPSITE, ORICK BEACH - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, Jan, and Rainey are beside a campfire, sitting on blankets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their tents loom behind them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan is weaving some sort of craft art.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is chomping on chicken and beans like they're going out of style.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (between large swallows)
{DIALOGUE}: So, I just left the car.
{DIALOGUE}: It was a great car too.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd driven it cross country the first time when I got out of high school.
{DIALOGUE}: I had some really great adventures with it.
{DIALOGUE}: That thing would just go and go.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, it was an `82 but if I'd kept it, it would've lasted me forever.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: So, you're a leather now.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a leather?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey nods, smiling.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (looking to Jan)
{DIALOGUE}: What's a leather?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: You're a leather tramp.
{DIALOGUE}: That's what they call the ones that hoof it on foot.
{DIALOGUE}: So, we're technically rubber tramps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 29.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{META_DATA}: (interjecting)
{DIALOGUE}: As we have a vee-hi-cle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey makes a move to put his arm around Jan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She goes a little stiff and fends it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris notices.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Alex could have a vehicle.
{DIALOGUE}: If he didn't burn his money.
{DIALOGUE}: Why would you want to do that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I don't need money.
{DIALOGUE}: It makes people cautious.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{META_DATA}: (a little irritated)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you have to be a little cautious Alex. That book of yours is all well and fine but you can't depend entirely on leaves and berries.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know if you'd want to depend on much more than that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Where's your mom and dad?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Makin' their money somewhere.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: Come on Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: You look like a loved kid.
{DIALOGUE}: Be fair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Fair?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I mean.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll paraphrase Thoreau -- "Rather than love, than money, than fairness, give me truth."
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: You look like shit.
{DIALOGUE}: There's the truth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They all laugh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 30.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 41 INT. CHRIS' TENT, ORICK BEACH - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits up reading, his tent entry flap ajar to let the small candle lantern ventilate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: OS we HEAR a ZIPPING SOUND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's Rainey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see him from Chris' POV coming out of his tent deep in thought.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he moves to the glowing embers of what remains of the campfire, Rainey's face goes out of frame and all Chris can see are his booted feet, tapping bits of glowing wood into the center of the fire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tapping is slow and thoughtful.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Micro-embers float upward into the night.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris' tent flap closes by his own hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Chris' dog-ears his book and puts out the lantern.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 42 EXT. ORICK BEACH - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris foraging for firewood in the bluffs above the beach.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's got it tied to his back and his front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: If we didn't know better, we'd think he was camouflaging himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris' POV: The rocks beside the water's edge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Rainey sitting beside the water, staring out to sea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow Chris' gaze to Jan, some fifty yards down the beach, walking melancholically in the opposite direction of Rainey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Rainey at the water's edge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris appears beside him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{META_DATA}: (regarding Chris wrapped up in wood)
{DIALOGUE}: Geez.
{DIALOGUE}: If I struck a match to you, I'd have warmth and dinner at the same time.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 31.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Rainey's humor does not hide an inner turmoil.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Where's Jan going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: Well, my friend, all is not well on the hippie front.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pulls out his pocketknife, cuts the twine that binds the firewood to his body, and takes a seat beside Rainey.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You're an industrious little fucker, aren't ya... Yeah, it's funny how things happen at particular times.
{DIALOGUE}: I've loved that woman for a lot of years.
{DIALOGUE}: But you know, she's got a..
{DIALOGUE}: story.
{DIALOGUE}: We've been going through this thing real quietly cause, well...So, after running into you last night, this thing we were going through quietly, she started talking about.
{DIALOGUE}: You know what I mean?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I think so.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: You think what?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is looking off at Jan walking in the distance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I think she's probably quietly disconnecting.
{DIALOGUE}: It doesn't feel right to her to be close to you if there's a hole of some kind somewhere else.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: That's a helluva insight.
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus!
{DIALOGUE}: ... You're not Jesus, are you?
{DIALOGUE}: You gonna walk on that water and get her back for me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Actually, I'm a little afraid of water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey gives him a sideways glance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: It's true.
{DIALOGUE}: But it's something I've got to get over sometime.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 32.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: So, I'll swim in it if you'll carry the firewood back to the campsite.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: I'll carry.
{DIALOGUE}: Shit-yes I'll carry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that, Chris runs down the beach toward Jan.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey watches Chris and Jan chat briefly.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then they strip down to their underwear and jump into the ocean, splashing and laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Rainey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A warmth comes over him, watching his old lady having some fun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grabs two armfuls of wood and heads to the campsite.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Chris and Jan swimming in the chilly water, having a ball.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan increasingly indulges herself a motherly closeness and joy with Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Chris allows it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She pushes the stringy hairs from his eyes, worries when he descends below the surface for too many seconds, and smiles and laughs in tender relief when from below surface one of her toes is pulled on by the big fish Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he re- surfaces, she gives him a splash right in the face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 43 EXT. CAMPSITE, ORICK BEACH - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through a burning campfire in the late afternoon, we see the chilly bodies of Chris and Jan carrying their clothes run shivering toward us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey sits beside the campfire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: I thought you guys might need a little heat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Jan smiles appreciatively.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: JAN
{META_DATA}: (moving to Rainey)
{DIALOGUE}: That's not hot enough.
{DIALOGUE}: Put your arms around me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they embrace, Chris throws a coat on from his tent, puts on his funny straw hat, and grabs a book.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Rainey has wrapped a blanket around Jan and they sit beside the fire.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 33.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to go down the beach a ways and read a little bit.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll bring the rest of that wood back before nightfall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RAINEY
{DIALOGUE}: Alright.
{DIALOGUE}: We might take a run into town to grab some food for tonight.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Sounds good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He heads off down the beach.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 44 EXT. ORICK BEACH MONTAGE
