{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 5.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Cooking the last of his rice on the Montana border.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 6.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hitchhiking in the Montana sunset.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 49 EXT. CUT BANK, MONTANA - SUNSET (SEPTEMBER 10 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris hitching down a lonely two-lane road surrounded by fields and distant mountains.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In early September, mom and dad got a call from the Annandale police notifying them that Chris' abandoned car had been identified by the Arizona Highway Patrol after a group of rare flower hunters stumbled upon it in the desert.
{DIALOGUE}: There were no signs that Chris had intended to return to it.
{DIALOGUE}: But there wasn't any evidence of struggle.
{DIALOGUE}: The police said they thought Chris had chosen to leave it behind and not that it had been taken from him.
{DIALOGUE}: Nonetheless, the initial comfort that gave mom and dad, quickly turned to their realization that Chris was actually trying not to be found.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 50 EXT. ANNANDALE STREET - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Walt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks out the door of his house into the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He keeps walking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And we go with him in his silent but internal Armageddon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PULL him in CU throughout all that follows...(Refer to SCENE 171: "Dad calls it `suspended animation.'"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This may affect our visual approach)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: The year Chris graduated high school he bought the Datsun, used.
{DIALOGUE}: He wanted to drive it cross-country and visit our old neighborhood in California.
{DIALOGUE}: The day before he left was my dad's birthday.
{DIALOGUE}: Chris made a speech...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 38.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 51 INT. MCCANDLESS HOME, ANNANDALE (PAST)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stands beside the family piano, speaking to a party of his parent's friends, Walt and Billie among them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beside him, a large gift-wrapped present.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine sits at the foot of the stairs at the back of the room watching her brother with a hint of concern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (a little drunk, a little emotional)
{DIALOGUE}: Dad, you and I have had our differences over the years...but on your birthday I want to tell you how grateful I am for all the things you've given me.
{DIALOGUE}: And that you did it starting from nothing to working your way through college and busting your ass to support us kids.
{DIALOGUE}: So, in return, I've been busting my ass a bit...at Domino's Pizza -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris moves to the gift.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: and I've gotten you this token, this damned expensive token, as a token of that appreciation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris holds the large gift toward Walt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt moves through his friends to Chris and strips the paper, exposing a beautiful Questar Telescope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{META_DATA}: (patting his son the back)
{DIALOGUE}: Would you look at that.
{DIALOGUE}: Walt holds the telescope up for all to see.
{DIALOGUE}: And the party responds with applause.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris walks through the cheering family friends to take his place beside Carine at the bottom of the steps.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Jesus, you must've had a lot to drink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Too much and not enough.
{DIALOGUE}: I used to believe all that stuff.
{DIALOGUE}: That whole story.
{DIALOGUE}: I thought maybe if I said it again, I'd believe it.
{DIALOGUE}: But I don't.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 39.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Tears have come to Chris' eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He puts his head in his hands.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine puts an arm around him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 52 EXT ANNANDALE STREET - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PRESENT: Walt expressionless, walking into camera.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The day after the party, Chris left on his trip and ended up staying away most of the summer.
{DIALOGUE}: It was nearly three months before he walked back into our house in Annandale.
{DIALOGUE}: He had a scruffy beard, his hair was long and tangled, and he was rail thin.
{DIALOGUE}: As soon as I heard he was home, I ran into his room to talk to him.
{DIALOGUE}: In California, he'd looked up some old family friends who still lived there.
{DIALOGUE}: He'd found out that long after he had been born, our dad had continued a relationship with his first wife Marcia in secret.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 53 EXT CUT BANK, MONTANA - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BRIEF CUTAWAY to Chris hitching on the Montana highway.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: And that one lie had led to another.
{DIALOGUE}: That two years after Chris was born, dad had had another son with Marcia.
{DIALOGUE}: Worse yet was that it was Marcia to whom he was still legally married at the time.
{DIALOGUE}: And it was Chris and I who were the bastard children.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 54 EXT ANNANDALE STREET - DUSK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Dad's arrogance made him conveniently oblivious to the pain he caused.
{DIALOGUE}: And mom, in the shame and embarrassment of a young mistress, became his accomplice.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 39aA.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: She and my dad had decided to bend the truth about this other child saying that dad wasn't the father and they maintained that their fraudulent marriage was real.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 39A.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Chris was quiet when he told me this.
{DIALOGUE}: He said it made his "entire childhood seem like a fiction"; that "the truth had been dying everyday."
{DIALOGUE}: If something bothered Chris, he'd usually keep it to himself.
{DIALOGUE}: And he made me promise to do the same.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 40.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: He never did tell mom and dad that he knew.
{DIALOGUE}: But Chris measured himself and those around him by an impossibly rigorous moral code.
{DIALOGUE}: He loathed what he considered mom and dad's hypocrisy and resented what they considered guidance.
{DIALOGUE}: Chris submitted to dad's authority through college but I knew he raged inwardly the whole time.
{DIALOGUE}: It was inevitable that Chris would rebel.
{DIALOGUE}: And when he did, he did it with characteristic immoderation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt suddenly collapses to his knees weeping, heartbroken and ashamed on a quiet Annandale street in the shadowless light of dusk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: My father is a brilliant man.
{DIALOGUE}: But he had made some terrible mistakes.
{DIALOGUE}: And to some extent, it seemed Chris was making him pay an awful price.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The image of Walt DISSOLVES INTO...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 55 EXT. CUT BANK, MONTANA (SEPTEMBER 10, 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A pick-up truck pulls over for Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Chris jumps in, we see on the passenger side door, the name WAYNE WESTERBERG boldly painted across it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris hops in beside a hyper kinetic man with thick shoulders and a black goatee.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: (rolling a cigarette without moving forward with the truck, his knees rattling up and down) How're you doing?
{DIALOGUE}: Wayne Westerberg.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (shaking hands)
{DIALOGUE}: Hi Wayne.
{DIALOGUE}: Alex McCandless.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: Seems like every time I come on this road, there's somebody hitching out here who looks as skinny and unfed as you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris nods with a laugh.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wayne continuing...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 41.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Look, I gotta stop in Ethridge to drop something off (know what I mean?)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is not sure about the "drop something off" part.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: How `bout you and I grab something to eat down there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, I wouldn't want to burden you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: How long has it been since you've had anything to eat?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Couple of days.
{DIALOGUE}: I kinda ran out of money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, there's no choice about it.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm gonna get you some dinner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wayne lights his cigarette, puts the truck in gear and they head down the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the sun dips behind the horizon we TILT UP off the departing truck to the sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ominously mounting clouds stunningly reflect the red rays of the hidden sun:
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 56 EXT. SUNBURST - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wayne's truck cuts through a track in a wheat field moving toward a compound of three trailers, one a double- wide, the other two on wheels, smaller.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Beside them, a Wyeth-esque farmhouse.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He eases the engine and comes to a stop in front of the double-wide.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he and Chris dismount the truck, Wayne gives him a hushing finger across the lips.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They tip-toe up to the door, where Wayne shuffles a bunch of keys.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A little thunder kicking in the distant sky.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 41A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 56A INT. DOUBLE-WIDE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Wayne and Chris enter, they tip-toe over empty booze bottles and passed out work crew; Wayne's harvesting team.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They make their way to a small table in the kitchenette.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Remains of the evening's dinner are on the stove.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wayne turns on the stovetop coils to heat it up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: So where is it you're headed?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I was thinking about doubling back through the Canadian side of Glacier Park.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I used to have a girlfriend who'd go there, camp on the Black Feet Res.
{DIALOGUE}: She was into all that American Indian stuff.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 42.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I can bring you to the border at Sweet Grass once you've had some food.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Well, that'd be great.
{DIALOGUE}: What do you do out here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I do a lot of things.
{DIALOGUE}: Computer programming.
{DIALOGUE}: Video game repair.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a licensed pilot, own a grain elevator in Carthage and another one a few miles out of town.
{DIALOGUE}: But in the summertime I run a combine crew, follow the harvest from Texas way the hell north to the Canadian border.
{DIALOGUE}: We just got done cutting barley for Coors and Anheuser Busch.
{DIALOGUE}: But then I got this little black box deal on the side (You know what I mean?)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You mean those free satellite TV deals?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE
{META_DATA}: (as though he hadn't brought it up)
{DIALOGUE}: You said it, not me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is dazzled by this renaissance man of the plains.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Wayne stands to dish out a couple of plates of heated food.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Chris starts digging in, a major gust of wind rocks the trailer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WAYNE (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (smiling, responding to wind)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: OOOOOOH.
{DIALOGUE}: Chris doesn't respond, digs into the food.
{DIALOGUE}: Points to the unconscious tribe splayed out.
{DIALOGUE}: SIX GERMANIC-LOOKING UNCONSCIOUS BODIES.
