{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 78 EXT. HIGHWAY BETWEEN CARTHAGE, SD AND THE GRAND CANYON - NIGHT (OCTOBER 28 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris has hitched a ride with a long-haul trucker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SERIES OF ANGLES: MUSIC OVER: Traveling shots.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 79 EXT. COLORADO RIVER, STRETCH OF THE GRAND CANYON - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris disembarks the long-haulers truck, waves a goodbye, and the truck moves on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SERIES OF ANGLES: Chris walking south through the desert following the river bank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He covers twelve miles before he arrives in an Arizona town, a dusty weigh-in station.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 80 EXT. ARIZONA TOWN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The town is quiet but along the storefront lane where Chris walks, he comes upon a sporting goods store.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the window, a fiberglass river kayak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stares at it.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 81 EXT. INTERSTATE UNDERPASS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR passing cars humming above.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris has set up camp and he's digging in the dirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He buries many of his belongings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He makes sure he's got his check from working with Wayne in his pocket.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He packs only the essential items, burying all else.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gets into his sleeping bag and goes to sleep.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 55.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 81A EXT. LEE'S FERRY ROAD - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris backpacks past the mushroom rock forms at the entrance of Lee's Ferry.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 82 INT. RANGER'S STATION - LEE'S FERRY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris approaches the GREEN-SUITED FUNCTIONARY at the front desk.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: Can I help you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: If I wanted to paddle down the river, where's the best place to launch out of?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: "To launch out of?"
{DIALOGUE}: What's your experience level?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Not much.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: Any?
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have a permit?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: A permit for what?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: You can't paddle down the river without a permit.
{DIALOGUE}: If you like, you can apply for one here, get yourself some experience, and I'll put you on the wait-list.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Wait-list?
{DIALOGUE}: To paddle down a river?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: That's right.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (giggling)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, how long do you have to wait?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: I've got an opening May 2003.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 56.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (laughing)
{DIALOGUE}: Twelve years?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN SUIT
{DIALOGUE}: Well, you could always join a commercial raft trip and go with a licensed guide.
{DIALOGUE}: They usually have a few last minute cancellations.
{DIALOGUE}: I think it's about two- thousand dollars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris busts a gut.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks for your help.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The Green Suit eyes Chris' departure with suspicion.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 83 EXT. COLORADO RIVER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stands beside a dramatic section of rapids.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The whitewater roars.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we SLOWLY ZOOM INTO Chris' face, terrified and absorbed by the torrent, a bead of sweat drops across his forehead, TILTS OUR CAMERA to his trembling hands and legs, when Peter Gabriel's I Have The Touch begins to play.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ZOOM INTO Chris' face...a decision: Fear becomes determination We SMASH CUT ON CUE with Peter Gabriel's vocals.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLO MO, SUPER DRAMATIC - Chris blasting out of a shoot in the rapids in the kayak we saw the night before.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's outrageous.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hair-raising.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just like Peter Gabriel sings it, he has the touch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This kid's never kayaked before, certainly never on rapids.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But it's that immortal stage of life, no care, no helmet, no life-jacket, pure adrenaline.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He can hardly believe he's surviving it as he goes but there's no looking back now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with every thump of the music, we share his rush.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His pure unadulterated exhilaration.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: With the culmination of the music, Chris has successfully shot the rapid.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He paddles through quiet waters.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 57.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We move in on him as he maneuvers the kayak to face upstream.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There before him, the impossible rapid he had just completed.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm Superman.
{DIALOGUE}: SuperTramp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He feels immortal.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He makes his about-face and is about to head down stream when he sees at the river's edge, a group of RIVER TOURISTS and their GUIDE lunching beside a pontoon raft.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The tourists look like a bunch of bewildered tubby-troopers in their misfitted orange life- vests and cereal bowl helmets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The RIVER GUIDE yells out at Chris as Chris moves PAST CAMERA and away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The guide gets on his satellite phone to alert the Rangers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We ZOOM SLOWLY away from them toward the rapid.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 84 EXT. ANOTHER QUIET SECTION OF RIVER - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Phillip Glass' Cloudscape plays OVER: Chris paddles on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LOW ANGLE: It is a narrow gorge of solid rock, looking up from hundreds of feet below the canyon crest.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 85 EXT. FURTHER ALONG THE RIVER - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The canyon has widened to beach-like banks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music FADES.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Along the banks he sees a YOUNG BLONDE COUPLE.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is MADS and SONJA, in their 20's, Danish.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They play at the river's edge beside their campsite, hotdogs cooking on a Hibachi.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris averts his eyes when Sonja rises from the water, topless.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{META_DATA}: (yelling out to Chris)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Hello.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: You can join us!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris doesn't know quite what to do.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Mads seems quite comfortable inviting a stranger into the presence of his topless girlfriend.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 58.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: We have hotdogs!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris - can't turn that down!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He paddles to within feet of the water's edge.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I am Mads.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Hi.
{DIALOGUE}: Alex.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{DIALOGUE}: I am Sonja.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris gives Sonja a little wave.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She bypasses it, wading up to the Kayak, giving him a big hug.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Hello Alex.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This couple is extremely energetic.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Can't wait to please.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And a bona fide American adventurer in their midst.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's everything they could've wanted.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: We are from Copenhagen.
{DIALOGUE}: And you are from the rapids.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{DIALOGUE}: My Got!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: Crazy man.
{DIALOGUE}: You're a crazy man!
{DIALOGUE}: Sonja, he is a crazy man.
{META_DATA}: (to Chris)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll make you a hotdog.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mads grabs a hotdog from the Hibachi.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Just one minute.
{DIALOGUE}: One minute...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sonja has moved to the tent to put on a dry T-shirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But as she moves back to the water's edge, those nipples keep saying Hello.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, meanwhile, simply cannot wipe the smile off his face in the presence of these warm, open people.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 59.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I love this.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you love this?
{DIALOGUE}: This is nature.
{DIALOGUE}: We see it in the American movies.
{DIALOGUE}: How come you're crazy?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Well...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: Because that's crazy!
{DIALOGUE}: You come down the rapids.
{DIALOGUE}: What do you want on your hotdog?
{DIALOGUE}: Mustard and relish?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You have ketchup?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: No, I have mustard and relish.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Mustard and relish it is then.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: Sonja, you want a hotdog?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{META_DATA}: (in Danish)
{DIALOGUE}: Of course I want a hotdog.
{DIALOGUE}: Why are you stupid?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mads plops two more hotdogs onto the grill.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{META_DATA}: (translating)
{DIALOGUE}: She asked me why I'm stupid.
{DIALOGUE}: And I say, well...like I ask you why you're crazy and you say "well."
{DIALOGUE}: Where are you going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I haven't decided.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: We like it here very much.
{DIALOGUE}: We went to Los Angeles.
{DIALOGUE}: And then, we went to Las Vegas.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{DIALOGUE}: Las Vegas is very nice.
{DIALOGUE}: The universe is very good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 59A.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: And then, we come here.
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe you go to Mexico.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 60.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: You can take kayak around Lake Mead and then take the river down to Mexico.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris likes the idea.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: How far are we from Lake Mead?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: Sonja, how far is Hoover Dam?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sonja grabs a map from the tent, opens and scrutinizes it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow her finger tracing the river.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{DIALOGUE}: Maybe three hundred thirty kilometers...like two hundred miles.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sonja walks the map over to Chris at water's edge and hands it to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He studies it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Man, I wonder if I could go all the way down into the Gulf of California.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris traces his finger along the impossibly long route leading to El Golfo de Santa Clara.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{META_DATA}: (entering the water with Chris' hotdog)
{DIALOGUE}: I go with you.
{DIALOGUE}: We leave Sonja here.
{DIALOGUE}: You and me in kayak - we go to Mexico.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{META_DATA}: (in Danish)
{DIALOGUE}: You're embarrassing.
{DIALOGUE}: Idiot.
{DIALOGUE}: Mads with a burst of re-exhilaration, grabs Chris' hand, shaking it violently.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: I like the meeting you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm very happy to meet both of you too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sonja heads back for her hotdog taking her T-shirt off on the move.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is about to bust a gut.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sonja returns to her sunbathing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: These two are a hoot.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 60A.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Just then, something catches Chris' attention upriver.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We can just barely make out the SOUNDS of a jet boat motor.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His eyes narrow a bit, then -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 61.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, guys I really appreciate the hospitality but I wanna make camp down- river a ways so I better take off before dark.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 86 EXT. COLORADO RIVER - MOMENTS LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, back in the kayak is paddling down river.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mads and Sonja on the bank, wave a boisterous goodbye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And they just keep waving.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Chris keeps waving until he has drifted out of sight, when around the upriver bend arrive the RIVER PATROL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At river's edge, Mads, thinking quickly, waves for their attention.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Pointing the river patrol back upriver, he yells:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: MADS
{DIALOGUE}: He went thattaway!
{DIALOGUE}: The crazy man - he went thattaway!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And miraculously, the river patrol makes an about face and heads in the opposite direction of Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly Sonja thinks Mads is the most clever man on earth.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As she jumps his bones right there on the river's edge -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SONJA
{DIALOGUE}: Just like in the movies.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 62.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 87 EXT. DESERT ROAD, NEAR HOOVER DAM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris and the kayak are in the back of a pick-up truck heading down river by road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We pass the Hoover Dam.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: It would be Christmas in a couple of months.
{DIALOGUE}: And the last news we'd had was about his car being found.
{DIALOGUE}: I woke up a couple of days ago, and for the first time, I was surprised to realize that it wasn't only my parents who hadn't heard from Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: I wondered why he hadn't tried to call in case I might answer.
{DIALOGUE}: He could've hung up if it wasn't me.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 88 EXT. COLORADO RIVER, TOPOCK, ARIZONA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is re-stocked on some food items which he packs in his bag and shoves into the bow of the kayak.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This lower stretch of the river has little in common with the unbridled torrent that explodes through the Grand Canyon.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Emasculated by dams and diversion canals, the lower Colorado burbles indolently from reservoir to reservoir, through some of the hottest, starkest, most austere country on the continent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 63.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: But why he didn't send a letter, maybe through a friend.
{DIALOGUE}: I got mad.
{DIALOGUE}: But I told myself it was good.
{DIALOGUE}: It made me remember that there was something more than rebellion, more than anger that was driving him.
{DIALOGUE}: Chris had always been driven, had always been an adventurer.
{DIALOGUE}: When he was four years old...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 89 EXT. DARK NEIGHBORHOOD STREET - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris at age four.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: ...he once wandered six blocks away from home at three o'clock in the morning.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 90 INT. NEIGHBOR'S KITCHEN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Four-year old Chris opening a kitchen drawer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: He was found in a neighbor's kitchen, up on a chair, digging into their candy drawer.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 91 EXT. COLORADO RIVER, TOPOCK ARIZONA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Chris paddles downstream with Mexico in his sights, he is stirred by the saline beauty and the clean slant of light.
{META_DATA}: (Director's Note: ANGLE over Chris ONTO water reflecting the landscape and diamond flashes of sunlight.)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Whatever drawer he was opening now must have something sweet in it.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 91A EXT. COLORADO RIVER, TOPOCK ARIZONA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris floats in SLO-MO through the air, his hair wisping skyward.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 63A.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he pierces feet first, a clear blue surface of the river's water, CAMERA goes UNDERWATER with him and follows him in CU as he surfaces, jubilant in the beauty of the Topock gorge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He shakes the water out of his hair.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 92 EXT. COLORADO RIVER, TOPOCK ARIZONA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 64.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris continuing down river through the Imperial National Wildlife Refuge, drifting past saguaros and alkali flats.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 92A EXT. IMPERIAL NATIONAL WILDLIFE REFUGE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, on a day hike, the river behind him, he (TELEFOTO LENS played in beautific BACK LIGHT) tracks a herd of wild horses.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Chris: The herd moves in an S-pattern.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris runs beside them and in our LONG LENS PERSPECTIVE, he seems to be among them.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 93 EXT. RIVER CAMPSITE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits outside his tent, beside a campfire scrawling a letter.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His "bought-food" bounty in evidence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The words APPEAR ON SCREEN in his handwriting OVER THE IMAGE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WAYNE, SOMETIMES I WISH I HADN'T MET YOU.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TRAMPING IS TOO EASY WITH ALL THIS MONEY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MY DAYS WERE MORE EXCITING WHEN I WAS PENNILESS AND HAD TO FORAGE AROUND FOR MY NEXT MEAL.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I COULDN'T MAKE IT NOW WITHOUT MONEY HOWEVER...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 94 EXT. YUMA POST OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CONTINUE letter OVER: ...AS THERE IS LITTLE FRUITING AGRICULTURE DOWN HERE AT THIS TIME.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris moves up the steps of the post office with an enveloped letter in hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CONTINUE letter OVER:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: I'VE DECIDED THAT I'M GOING TO LIVE THIS LIFE FOR SOME TIME TO COME.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: THE FREEDOM AND SIMPLE BEAUTY OF IT IS JUST TOO GOOD TO PASS UP...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 65.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 95 INT YUMA POST OFFICE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is in the elegant, 1930's-style post office buying a stamp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CONTINUE letter OVER:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ONE DAY I'LL BE ABLE TO REPAY SOME OF YOUR KINDNESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A CASE OF JACK DANIELS, MAYBE?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TILL THEN, I'LL ALWAYS THINK OF YOU AS A FRIEND...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris licks the stamp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Continue letter on screen:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: GOD BLESS YOU, ALEXANDER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The stamp comes down onto an envelope addressed:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WAYNE WESTERBERG
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: C/O GLORY HOUSE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SIOUX FALLS WORK RELEASE FACILITY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SIOUX FALLS, SD 57104
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 95A EXT. THE SAND DUNES ON THE AMERICAN SIDE OF MEXICAN BORDER - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris ports his kayak over the dunes, snaking a scar through the sand in his wake.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mexico in his sights.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: POV: Morelos Dam at the Mexican border.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 96 EXT. MORELOS DAM AT THE MEXICAN BORDER - DAY (DECEMBER 2ND, 1990)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Careful not to be seen, Chris shoves off, just upriver from the dam/border.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The floodgates are open just enough to allow Chris to lay back in the kayak and drift prone under the gate.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He sits back up and paddles through having passed the border, either unnoticed or ignored by patrols.
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 65A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 97 INT. IMMIGRATION OFFICE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A television set with George Bush plays.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SOUNDS of typewriters.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: IMMIGRATION OFFICER (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Why'd you go to Mexico?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I thought I'd run the whole river into the Sea of Cortez.
{DIALOGUE}: The stupid dams dried it up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 66.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 98 EXT. 50 MILES SOUTH OF THE MEXICAN BORDER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is kayaking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He dead ends in a reeded tributary.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 99 OMITTED
{META_DATA}: 100 INT. IMMIGRATION OFFICE (CONTINUED)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: IMMIGRATION OFFICER (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: How long were you on your own down there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: 36 days.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: IMMIGRATION OFFICER (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: How'd you know?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Fingers and toes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris' fingers and toes.
{META_DATA}: (DOWN ANGLE into interrogation room)
