{DIALOGUE}: After the river dried up, I ported the kayak and got a lift to Golfo.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 101 EXT. FISHING VILLAGE, EL GOLFO DE SANTA CLARA - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris jump down off the back of the duck hunter's truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He slides the kayak off the truck bed onto the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris goes into his pocket, pulls out a sealed sandwich bag of cash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He tries to pay the hunters for their time but they refuse the money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Nonetheless, Chris is insistent and they relent.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pulls his backpack from inside the bow and saddles it up on his shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The hunters pull away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 67.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 102 EXT. EL GOLFO DE SANTA CLARA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: (1000mm lens) LOW ANGLE: SAND AND HEAT WAVES IN FOREGROUND AND BACKGROUND: Chris, paddling his kayak toward us, seemingly in the sand dunes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we BOOM UP SLIGHTLY, we see that there is a bend in the water's edge and that he is in fact, paddling in the crystalline blue of the Gulf.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I paddled south about 20 miles.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 103 EXT. EL GOLFO DE SANTA CLARA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: UNDER-WATER SHOT: We are directly UNDER the passing kayak as it slices the water's surface above us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We BACKFLIP the CAMERA as it passes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: That's when I saw the cave and everything went upside down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 68.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 104 EXT. EL GOLFO DE SANTA CLARA
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: See the ocean and sand, wind whipping them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CAMERA PULLS BACK to reveal Chris in a cave where he has made camp; watching, waiting.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A sandstorm hit and I was pretty much stuck.
{DIALOGUE}: My kayak blew away, so I left it and walked up the beach, hitched back north, and here I am.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 105 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 106 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 69.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 107 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 108 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 109 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 110 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 111 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 70.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 112 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 113 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 114 OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 115 INT. IMMIGRATION OFFICE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits with the IMMIGRATION OFFICER.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 71.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: IMMIGRATION OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: 36 days, wow.
{DIALOGUE}: I guess they're gonna have to watch that spillway a little better.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: What they ought to do is open up the dams and let the rivers flow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: IMMIGRATION OFFICER
{DIALOGUE}: I can't disagree with you on that.
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Alexander SuperTramp.
{DIALOGUE}: I think we're gonna let you out of here shortly but you've got two working weeks to get an ID card in the United States.
{DIALOGUE}: You can't be crossing these borders without identification, are we understood?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{DIALOGUE}: I've eaten enough sand to send me back to the city anyway.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 116 EXT. TRAIN YARD, SOMEWHERE NEAR ALGODONES - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A freight train cranks up its great engines and starts its move west.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris POV: We see a BULL (hobo slang for a railway security guard) making his rounds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the bull disappears around the caboose, and the trains motion picks up, Chris appears from behind a fuel pump.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He makes his move in the shadows to the passing freight cars, not quite sure how to board them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins to slowly jog beside the train.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There is a vertical steel rod on each passing car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He times the train by putting his hand out and letting the vertical rods slap it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (counting)
{DIALOGUE}: One...Two...Three -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 71A.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that he accelerates to a run, throws his pack into the moving freight car before him, simultaneously leaping up to grab the rail and throw himself into the car.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 72.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But his left foot misses and he's suddenly dangling from the moving train.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He grabs hand over hand on the rail.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Dangling feet and razor sharp wheels.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He puts everything into pulling himself up, growling the strength into his muscles finally...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 117 INT. FREIGHT CAR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Chris rolls forward into the car -- he made it!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: As Alexander Supertramp returns to civilization...a hobo.
{META_DATA}: (quietly)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm a for real hobo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's very happy about this (despite the near surrender of it.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris uses his pack as a pillow, lays back on it and begins to sing Roger Miller's King of the Road.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 118 EXT. FREIGHT TRAIN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We TRACK with train by HELICOPTER as we SEGUE from Chris' rendition of King of the Road to Roger Miller's.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We let the train get away from us and disappear.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 119 EXT. TRAIN YARD, LOS ANGELES - DAY (FEBRUARY 3, 1991)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris' train pulls into the yard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Bulls and loaders greet the train.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris jumps off and breaks for the fence unseen.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 120 OMITTED
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 73.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 121 EXT. DOWNTOWN LOS ANGELES - EARLY EVENING (STILL LIGHT)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The streets are crowded with business people on their way to homes and happy hours, buses and parking garages, showers and comforts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Among the throngs, we find Chris walking up Grand Street, backpack on his shoulders.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We find he is not such an unusual sight, there are homeless to the left and homeless to the right.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 122 EXT. MIDNIGHT MISSION, LOS ANGELES - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris walks in.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 123 INT. REGISTRATION DESK, MIDNIGHT MISSION - SAME
{META_DATA}: (Reminder: Condition of Mission is circa 1991)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stands at the registration desk talking with a a HEAVY-SET BLACK FEMALE SOCIAL WORKER.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Can you tell me how to get an ID card?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 74.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: Did you lose your identification sir?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: No birth certificate?
{DIALOGUE}: Nothing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris shakes his head apologetically.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Ouch.
{DIALOGUE}: Alright.
{DIALOGUE}: Well you're gonna have to work that out with the DMV.
{DIALOGUE}: You can catch them in the morning.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The social worker begins to write an address on a piece of paper.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: The closest one is Montebello and we can help you with a bus voucher.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She hands the Montebello address to Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: So, just come to this desk when you need the voucher.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: And, if I want to apply for a job somewhere, can you help me with that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: If you know how to cook, we might have a space for you in our mobile kitchen.
{DIALOGUE}: But I'll have to talk to my supervisor about it in the morning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alright then.
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, one last thing.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you have a bed for me?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER
{META_DATA}: (handing him a form)
{DIALOGUE}: Sure.
{DIALOGUE}: Just fill this in and I'll get you all set up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris begins filling in the form.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 75.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 124 INT. MIDNIGHT MISSION DORM, LOS ANGELES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Throughout the next two scenes, there is steady HONKING of CAR HORNS, WAILING of POLICE SIRENS, AMBIENT HOSTILE BANTER, GRINDING ENGINES OF BUSES, puffs of diesel exhaust choke us.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 300 HOMELESS occupy nearly as many beds in the dorm.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris searches the locker wall for his assigned locker.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When he comes upon it, he double checks the number with that on the key, opens it, and puts his backpack inside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CU: The lock, as Chris closes and secures his locker.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 125 EXT. LOS ANGELES STREETS - 6TH AND WALL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris walking among the hordes of homeless at 6th and Wall streets.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Open fires burn in front of cardboard shacks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There are blacks, whites, Mexicans, even families with children, junkies, winos, hustlers, and hookers.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 126 EXT. LOS ANGELES STREETS - BROADWAY - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NEW ANGLE: Chris walking down Broadway.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is clearly just blocks away from where we last saw him, yet the atmosphere is as if of a different world.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of those downtown LA hip yuppie blocks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He comes upon a bar.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the window Chris sees young men and women roughly his own age - working people, suits, gold-chainers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Metallica blares on the sound system.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 127 INT. MIDNIGHT MISSION DORM, LOS ANGELES
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Same CU on locker as before, but this time it's being opened.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 75A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 128 INT. REGISTRATION DESK, MIDNIGHT MISSION
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We don't even see Chris but the camera is his POV as he passes the social worker (same as before) The social worker catches a thrown key.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 76.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SOCIAL WORKER
{DIALOGUE}: You leaving us so soon?
{DIALOGUE}: I know them DMV lines are long...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 129 EXT. MIDNIGHT MISSION, LOS ANGELES - NIGHT
{META_DATA}: (Director's Note: Traffic and pedestrians move in an accelerated speed while Chris moves nearly in slo- motion.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris exits the building into CU.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks left, then right, then directly into camera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CHAPTER 3: MANHOOD
{META_DATA}: FADE OUT/IN:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 130 OMITTED
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 131 EXT. TRAIN TRACKS OUTSIDE LOS ANGELES - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris' train barrels along.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 132 INT. TRAIN CAR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris goes into his pack, grabs his canteen and drinks some water.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Mid-sip, the train begins to make a surprising stop.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Screeching wheels on track.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is alarmed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he moves to peer out the door, even before he has a chance to see what's coming -- WHAM!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's smashed in the head with a baton.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A BULL jumps into the car with him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2
{DIALOGUE}: Lay down on your stomach, spread eagle!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 77.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris turns to reason with the man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And that's all it takes -- six straight blows to the ribs, legs, and arms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We hear it more than we see it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is in agony.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2 (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Let me see your face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bull shines a flashlight into Chris' eyes.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2 (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I never, ever, ever forget a face.
{DIALOGUE}: If I see yours again, I won't arrest you.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll kill you.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the god-damned railroad.
{DIALOGUE}: And we will do whatever we have to, to keep you freeloaders from violating our liability.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is trying to understand what the man is saying.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2 (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: If one of you people gets hurt on our train, we are liable.
{DIALOGUE}: Do you understand that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (despite the violent irony)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm sorry, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2
{DIALOGUE}: You have I.D.?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: No, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2
{DIALOGUE}: Of course you don't.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 133 EXT. TRAIN - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is pushed off the train, his pack thrown out after him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The bull jumps down beside the track as well and walks down track away from Chris, signalling an "all clear" with his flashlight to some unseen engineer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BULL #2
{META_DATA}: (to Chris over his shoulder)
{DIALOGUE}: Last time, my friend.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 78.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stumbles to his feet.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The pain of the beating is real.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He bleeds from the back of his ear.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But he can walk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And he does.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 134 EXT. DESERT HIGHWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sits on his pack on the roadside, hitchhiking and eating from a can of beans he opened with his pocketknife.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The odd car passes but doesn't stop.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 135 EXT. ARIZONA INTERSTATE OVERPASS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris hops out of a Camaro that gave him a ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The lighting is anonymous and so is the driver.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks very much.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He closes the door and the car drives off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow Chris as he goes to the overpass edge.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He drops his pack over the side.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris climbs down the edge of the overpass, grabs his pack, and scurries into the UNDERPASS below.
{META_DATA}: (We suddenly recognize this as his pre-river run campsite)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He digs up his buried belongings, returning them to his pack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Last to come out of the ground, Chris' copy of Jack London's Call of the Wild.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls off a temp wrapping and dusts it off.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris lights his candle lantern and begins to read.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: O.S. VOICES from the PAST:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE (O.S.)
{META_DATA}: (screaming, angry)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not talking about this anymore!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Feet stomping off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Don't walk away from me WOMAN!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: Fuck you!
{DIALOGUE}: I hate you!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Sounds of scuffle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 78A.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE (O.S.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: KIDS!
{DIALOGUE}: LOOK WHAT YOUR FATHER'S DOING TO ME!
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 136 INT. MCCANDLESS HOME, ANNANDALE (PAST)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ELEVEN-YEAR OLD CARINE sits in the stairwell leading to her parent's room where an argument ensues.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine's head in her hands, a delicate tear moistens the webs between her small fingers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 79.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FIFTEEN-YEAR OLD CHRIS enters from O.S.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He leans against the stairwell and looks up the stairs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Our focus remains on Carine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the B.G. SOFT FOCUS, Walt is pinning Billie down onto the bed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She flails at him but he holds down her shoulders.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: LOOK WHAT YOUR MOTHER IS MAKING ME DO!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Billie slips his grasp.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Walt reaches out with a hit/push of her back.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She is thrust out of the bedroom onto the landing above the staircase followed by Walt who positions himself in the doorway like a hostile crucifixion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (raging)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll just cancel Christmas then!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Billie returns to him, punching on his chest:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE
{DIALOGUE}: Who do you think you are?
{DIALOGUE}: God?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm God!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris puts his hand out to Carine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks up to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He gives her a smile and a wink.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She takes his hand and they exit frame as the argument continues.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: WALT (O.S.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Where do you kids think you're going?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BILLIE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: (not in desperation so much as a demand for their witness) Kids, get back here!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR a DOOR SLAM OC.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 137 EXT. ANNANDALE STREET - DAY (PAST)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The young Chris and Carine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sits atop the handlebars of his bicycle beaming as Chris peddles her down the middle of the street.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PULL THEM as they ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 79aA.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (mockingly)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll cancel Christmas!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 79A.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{META_DATA}: (humored out of her sadness)
{DIALOGUE}: Who do you think you are?
{DIALOGUE}: God?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yes.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm God.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 80.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 138 EXT. ARIZONA INTERSTATE UNDERPASS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they both laugh we DISSOLVE BACK to Chris (PRESENT) reading beside his candle lantern.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In the nine months since Chris' disappearance, my parents went through enormous changes.
{DIALOGUE}: Guilt was giving way to pain.
{DIALOGUE}: And pain seemed to bring them closer.
{DIALOGUE}: My father had humbled dramatically.
{DIALOGUE}: And what had always been a sort of curt arrogance, the kind of man who actually thought he could cancel Christmas, had given way to the vulnerability of a father's heart.
{DIALOGUE}: Even their faces had changed.
{DIALOGUE}: It made me sad that I couldn't share with Chris the new closeness I felt toward our parents.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The image of Chris reading begins a SLOW DISSOLVE INTO...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 139 INT. FREIGHT TRAIN CAR - NIGHT
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: I close my eyes at night sometimes and imagine where Chris might be.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suspicious, ghostly faces briefly appear in the strobing lights that hit the train car from outside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're toothless and tattooed.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Aged and young.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Punks and piercings.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They're train tramps.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris observing them.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Warmly he speaks but we DO NOT HEAR, "I'm Alex."
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 140 EXT. TRAMP CAMP, LAS VEGAS - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Was there beauty around him?
{DIALOGUE}: Was he hurt?
{DIALOGUE}: Was he alone?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris sharing camp with the train tramps in the outskirts of Las Vegas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DISSOLVE...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 80A.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 141 INT. LAS VEGAS RESTAURANT - NIGHT
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Was he having the great adventure that he wanted?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris working as a waiter in a Las Vegas restaurant.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: DISSOLVE...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 81.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 142 EXT. MOUNTAIN PASS - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Could he feel the changes here at home?
{DIALOGUE}: By some kind of supernatural osmosis?
{DIALOGUE}: Chris once wrote to me from college saying he wanted to talk to me about all the problems he had with mom and dad.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see what may be Chris' POV from a train car snaking through a mountain pass.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 143 EXT. LAS VEGAS DESERT - NIGHT
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: He said I was the only person in the world who could've possibly understood what he had to say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris in the Las Vegas desert by a campfire at night.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 144 EXT. SEATTLE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HIGH ANGLE CU: We see Chris walking the streets of Seattle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we WIDEN OUT, he becomes a dot in the Seattle landscape.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: In those silent moments, with my eyes closed trying to picture where Chris might be at that very moment, probably climbing some scary mountain, I want to reach into that picture and bring him back to see what mom and dad, what our family might become.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LONG LENS: Chris disappears over the rise into the Seattle marketplace overlooking Puget Sound (per location photography.)
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 82.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 145 EXT. ANNANDALE SUPERMARKET - DAY
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: But instead when I open my eyes, what I see is my mother, sitting at the dining room table, sifting through photo albums and pictures of Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all she can do to examine the snapshots.
{DIALOGUE}: And, though she breaks down from time to time, she studies them with a sort of hungry intensity - like looking at food you can't eat, or into a window at a family around a table that you were once a part of and can be no more.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Billie driving out of the Annandale supermarket onto the boulevard.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She sees a hitchhiker roadside.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She cranes her head - is it Chris?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's not.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.) (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: She convinces herself it's Chris; that it's her son, whenever she passes a stray.
{DIALOGUE}: And I fear for the mother in her...
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 146 EXT. BARREN DESERT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Chris hitchhiking in a barren desert.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: Instincts that seem to sense the threat of a loss so huge and irreparable that the mind balks at taking its measure - I begin to wonder if I do understand what Chris is saying any longer.
{DIALOGUE}: But I catch myself in doubt and remember that these are not the parents he grew up with.
{DIALOGUE}: That in the forced reflection that comes with loss, indeed everything Chris is saying, has to be said.
{DIALOGUE}: And I trust for him that everything he is doing has to be done.
{DIALOGUE}: This is our life.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 83.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 147 EXT. BULLHEAD CITY, ARIZONA - DAY (OCTOBER 1991)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is in the passenger seat of a Mac truck cab.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both Chris and the TRUCKER look outward as though to find an address or landmark.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TRUCKER
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know where to drop you.
{DIALOGUE}: Bullhead's kinda haphazard - there's no "center."
{DIALOGUE}: You sure you don't want to be in Laughlin?
{DIALOGUE}: It's casinos versus chiropractors.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, no.
{DIALOGUE}: This is good.
{DIALOGUE}: Right here.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TRUCKER
{DIALOGUE}: Alright then.
{DIALOGUE}: Chiropractors it is.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pulls over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris grabs his pack and exits the truck in front of a laundromat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the truck pulls away, Chris sees a "Help Wanted" sign for Burger King on the laundromat window.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TIME CUT:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 148 INT. BURGER KING, BULLHEAD CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place is packed with a line out the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: LORI, the second assistant manager, hurries back into the kitchen, where we find Chris in paper cap, bunning whoppers at a leisurely pace.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{DIALOGUE}: Chris, you gotta go faster.
{DIALOGUE}: We've got a line out the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (a bit oblivious)
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But then just continues on at his leisurely daydreaming pace.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lori is about to say something but by now she knows there's no getting through to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: She looks down to the floor where we see that Chris wears no socks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{META_DATA}: (extending patience)
{DIALOGUE}: Chris, I don't mean to be on you about everything.
{DIALOGUE}: You're doing a great job.
{META_DATA}: (MORE)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 84.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I want to keep you on.
{DIALOGUE}: And we all want to help you get to Alaska, but you've got to start wearing socks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Right, right.
{DIALOGUE}: I forgot.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{DIALOGUE}: And please.
{DIALOGUE}: Hurry.
{DIALOGUE}: We're ten deep.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But the pace remains.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 149 INT. BANK, BULLHEAD CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris stands at the counter making a deposit with a YOUNG FEMALE TELLER.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: How much do I have in the account now?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: TELLER
{DIALOGUE}: It looks like...let me see.
{DIALOGUE}: Including this latest deposit...One thousand, two hundred and fifty two dollars and...twenty-two cents.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: What's the interest on twenty-two cents?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The young teller giggles.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 150 EXT. BANK, BULLHEAD CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We're TIGHT ON Chris' sock-less feet, pedalling away from the bank on a bicycle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The growing independence of his financial situation felt in the MUSIC OVER:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SERIES OF ANGLES as Chris rides out of town, into the desert, from a late afternoon sun into a sunset as he arrives at his -
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 151 EXT. CAMPSITE, OUTSIDE BULLHEAD CITY - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The casino lights of Laughlin, Nevada distantly in B.G.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 85.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pedals up a dirt path to find many of his belongings strewn about.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And in particular, some food supplies have been torn into.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A coyote yips in the distance as Chris finds his old straw hat torn to shreds.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Across the desert, scurrying away beyond the tumbleweed, three young coyotes head for the hills.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris picks up his tattered hat and smiles.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 152 INT. BURGER KING, BULLHEAD CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We are TIGHT on the PUNCHCLOCK as Chris' timecard comes into frame and is punched out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDEN OUT to see Chris taking off his paper hat and Burger King overshirt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks his timecard over to Lori.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The place is all but empty.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Lori, I'm punching out.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{DIALOGUE}: Okay.
{DIALOGUE}: Just put it in the drop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: No, I mean I'm punching out for good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{META_DATA}: (happy for him)
{DIALOGUE}: We've made our quota, have we?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: Also, I've got to do some things before I head north.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{DIALOGUE}: Alright Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: Well, we've enjoyed knowing you.
{DIALOGUE}: I won't be able to get that last check to you right away though.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: That's okay.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll let you know where to send it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: LORI
{DIALOGUE}: Alright then Chris.
{DIALOGUE}: Bye-bye now.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 86.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Bye-bye.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 153 EXT. BULLHEAD CITY - DAY
