{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 169 EXT. TWO-LANED ROAD, ANNANDALE, VA (PAST) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TELEPHOTO LENS: A long two-laned road before us rises and falls in a series of saddles and peaks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The narrow shoulders are densely wooded.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLOWLY APPEARING over the near most peak, a TEAM OF EIGHT SHIRTLESS HIGH SCHOOL RUNNERS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Leading the group - 17 YEAR-OLD CHRISTOPHER MCCANDLESS.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Lean, softly handsome, and graceful.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In high school, Chris became captain of the cross-country track team.
{DIALOGUE}: They called themselves the Road Warriors.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: REVERSE ANGLE: The group of young runners, led by Chris suddenly veer off the paved road into the adjoining woods.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 170 EXT. TRAILS, ANNANDALE (PAST) - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SERIES OF ANGLES: The runners, led by Chris, pace unchartered trails, grassy hillsides, and shallow streams.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE
{DIALOGUE}: He'd take them on what he loved to refer to as "epic" runs.
{DIALOGUE}: The whole point was to run until they were completely lost and so exhausted that they were on the verge of puking.
{DIALOGUE}: Then they'd slow down a little, somehow he'd find their bearings, and lead them home again at full speed.
{DIALOGUE}: This was my brothers idea of fun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We FAVOR Chris as he jogs in place at the exhilarating point of being lost.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When he has identified a most likely return route, he quickens his pace, leading the group in the direction of return.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 98.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 171 INT. MARKET/POST OFFICE, SALTON CITY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris heads out with his last Burger King check in hand, proudly wearing his new hat and in search of mountains to climb.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A year and a half into Chris' disappearance, each day that goes by now feels like two.
{DIALOGUE}: Dad calls it "suspended animation."
{DIALOGUE}: I kept telling myself that he had to get lost to prove his independence to himself.
{DIALOGUE}: But this was no day run for the Road Warriors and after so much time, I could no longer keep out the haunting thoughts.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 172 EXT. MARKET/POST OFFICE, SALTON CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, with pack and new hat walks away from camera toward the interstate and the brittle mountains beyond.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CARINE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: In many ways, my life and even my parents had begun to move in new directions.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd fallen in love.
{DIALOGUE}: And mom and dad had even ventured out on a brief vacation.
{DIALOGUE}: But, when a search of tax records uncovered Chris' contribution to OXFAM, the weight of his disappearance just seemed to lie down on us full length.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: CHAPTER 5: GETTING OF
{META_DATA}: WISDOM DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 173 EXT. BADLANDS OF ANZA-BORREGO DESERT STATE PARK - DAY
{META_DATA}: (JANUARY 1992)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 99.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: WIDE SHOT: We see the Oh My God Hot Springs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Steaming pools lined with rocks and shaded by palm trees.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A small group of campers and Charlie Manson wannabes in FOREGROUND.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We ZOOM past them to the sheer rock faces and landforms of the badlands, several miles beyond.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 174 EXT. STONE WALL, ANZA-BORREGO DESERT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SLO MO: We are looking down a radically steep rock face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A shirtless Chris is in training running towards us under the hot desert sun.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR only breath and footsteps.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 175 EXT. CHRIS' CAMP BESIDE THE STONE WALL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris rests on the sand under a tarp, hung from a Creosote branch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A plate of beans and rice eaten nearly clean and an empty water jug beside him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Flies buzz and pick.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 176 EXT. OH-MY-GOD HOT SPRINGS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris on a morning jog, wearing a shoulder bag and carrying an empty water jug.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A quick wave to one of his distant "neighbors" at the spring's camp as he runs by.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 177 EXT. PAVED TWO-LANE ROAD INTO SALTON CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris continues his jog, cars whisk by and dust kicks into the air.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But Chris is undeterred, keeps running.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 178 EXT. MARKET/POST OFFICE, SALTON CITY - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris approaches, slowing his jog to a walk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris sets down his water jug and stretches his calves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the distance we see the peaks of the badlands landforms from where he ran.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 100.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris shakes off the jog, picks up the jug, and we go with him around the side of the building.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: There's a water faucet dripping slowly into the desert mud.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pops his jug under it and fills it up.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 179 INT. MARKET/POST OFFICE - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris walks the aisles, sipping from his jug, as he comes across bags of rice on the market shelves.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A HEAVY SET GIRL passes him in the aisle with her well-mannered dog following her.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (no high-pitched pet voice)
{DIALOGUE}: Hey boy.
{DIALOGUE}: You are a handsome fellow.
{META_DATA}: (over shoulder to the girl)
{DIALOGUE}: Beautiful dog.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: THE GIRL
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As the girl continues on, the dog wants to stay with Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Go on, boy.
{DIALOGUE}: Go on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And the dog obeys him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he sorts through the various rice selections, brown, white, wild, we notice a MAN peering over the opposite shelf at Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This is RON FRANZ, between 70 and 80 years old, six-feet, thick arms, barrel chest, and large ears.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He wears old jeans, an immaculate white T-shirt, a decorative tooled leather belt, white socks, and scuffed black loafers.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His deeply pitted nose demonstrates a purple filigree of veins which unfold like an finely wrought tattoo.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And on either side of it, the wary blue eyes of a soldier.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is the archetypical American man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris has caught his sympathetic eye.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris moves to the counter to pay for rice.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 180 EXT. MARKET/POST OFFICE - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In WIDE SHOT, we watch Chris from behind, walking out across the two-lane road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He puts out his thumb to hitch a ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 101.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: When a truck comes from BEHIND INTO FRAME heading straight for Chris, the truck makes a relaxed L-turn, pulling up beside Chris.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 181 INT. RON'S TRUCK
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Where's your camp?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (pointing)
{DIALOGUE}: Out past Oh-My-God Hot Springs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I've lived in and around here six years now and I've never heard of any place that goes by that name.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron leans across the bench seat of the truck, opening up the passenger door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Show me how to get there.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris hops in beside Ron, who extends his hand -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Ron Franz.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alex.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Alex. Where are you from Alex?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: West Virginia.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Okay, Alex from West Virginia.
{DIALOGUE}: I like a fellow who doesn't raise the pitch of his voice when he talks to animals...shows he doesn't condescend.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris remembers now the dog in the store and why Ron must've thought to give him a ride.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And they head off.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 182 EXT. FEW MILES UP ROAD
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron truck drives up the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 102.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 183 INT. RON'S TRUCK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we come upon a 4x4 track twisting down a narrow wash -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You go left here.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron turns the truck down the 4x4 track.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 184 EXT. 4X4 TRACK, ANZA-BORREGO DESERT - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We watch the truck bump and grind on the mangled dirt road about a mile in.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Out the window, Ron's eye has been caught by something.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron's POV: Oh-My-God Hot Springs -
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a couple of day-glo vans and rusted out Studebakers that hadn't been turned over since Eisenhower was in the White House.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several of those living there mill about buck naked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And at the center of the camp, the steaming pools lined with rocks under the palm trees.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: You live here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: No, we keep going.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm further up.
{DIALOGUE}: Another half-mile or so, out on the Bajada.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 185 EXT. CHRIS' CAMP BESIDE THE STONE WALL - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron and Chris drive up in the truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron shuts off the ignition and gets out of the truck to stretch his legs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris follows, puts his full water jug under the tarp at his campsite, hooking it onto a branch.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He throws his shoulder bag with the rice in it into his backpack.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Well, this is somethin' out here.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't you worry about those dope smokers and nudists down below there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: No, they keep to themselves pretty much and so do I.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 103.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{META_DATA}: (skeptical)
{DIALOGUE}: Hmmm.
{DIALOGUE}: You strike me as a bright young man.
{DIALOGUE}: Am I wrong about that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I think I got my head on my shoulders pretty good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: That's what I mean.
{DIALOGUE}: How long have you been out here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Couple of weeks.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: And before that?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: A lot of places.
{DIALOGUE}: I've been moving around.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: How old are you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty-three.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Twenty-three years old!
{DIALOGUE}: Son, don't you think you should be getting an education?
{DIALOGUE}: And a job?
{DIALOGUE}: And making something of this life?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Look Mr. Franz.
{DIALOGUE}: I think careers are a twentieth century invention and I don't want one.
{DIALOGUE}: You don't need to worry about me.
{DIALOGUE}: I have a college education.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not destitute.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm living like this by choice.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: In the dirt?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (laughs)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, in the dirt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I just don't know.
{DIALOGUE}: Where's your family?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 104.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Don't have one anymore.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: That's a shame.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris can see some deep sadness in this man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, Mr. Franz.
{DIALOGUE}: I want to show you something.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron follows Chris to the rockface we'd seen Chris running earlier.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They begin to walk up it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's tough on the old-timer, walking this steep hill.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But he's a tough old- timer, at least for the moment...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: The two men nearly half way to the summit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's getting steeper and higher.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron stops.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: This is getting a little steep.
{DIALOGUE}: And a little high for me kid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Alright.
{DIALOGUE}: But look out there.
{DIALOGUE}: Even from half way out, it's quite a sight isn't it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Their POV: Enormous beautiful vista all the way across the Bajada.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: From the top you can see all the way to the Salton Sea too.
{DIALOGUE}: Ron looks up the precarious rock wall.
{DIALOGUE}: He ain't gonna be seeing the Salton Sea today.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: You can see the Salton Sea from up there?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{META_DATA}: (starting his way down the hill)
{DIALOGUE}: My goodness.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You don't want to go up?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 105.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Nope.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't do these kind of things.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris smiles and follows Ron.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As they approach the bottom of the hill -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: How about you and me take a drive?
{DIALOGUE}: About fifty miles or so up highway, I know a place that's got a view, great food, and requires no climbing.
{DIALOGUE}: How's that sound?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris thinks about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Then -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, sure.
{DIALOGUE}: It'll take me a couple of minutes to clean up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Fair enough.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 186 EXT. DESERT HIGHWAY - AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron's truck drives through frame.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 187 EXT. INDIAN AVENUE SOUTHBOUND, PALM SPRINGS - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see Ron and Chris driving parallel on the windmilled road (Our frame will only hold the lower fraction of the spinning windmills in the background)
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 188 EXT. SAN JACINTO TRAMWAY - LATE AFTERNOON
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: VERTICAL POV: We are thousands of feet in the air over the rigid rocky canyon as we ascend toward San Jacinto summit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It's high.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Scary HIGH.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 189 INT. TRAM
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MUSIC OVER: As Chris and Ron ride the tram to the peak, we watch Chris watching Ron, his kind, moist old eyes, slowly blinking at the wonder of the nature around him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Other passengers on the tram seem nervous, but Ron is meditative, almost hypnotized.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 106.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with each roll-through of the tram through the cable towers, the tram car rocks and sways, but Ron's peace goes unbroken.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Chris continues to admire the gentle blinking of his eyes.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 190 INT. ELEVATION RESTAURANT (SAN JACINTO SUMMIT) - TWILIGHT90 1
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The two of them sit in a quiet, corner booth of the tramway eatery that sits on the summit of San Jacinto overlooking the lights of Palm Springs and the desert clear back to Salton Sea.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is on a roll.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: How old are you, Mr. Franz?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Seventy-nine years old.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Seventy-nine...see, all due respect, but the real difference between people is the quality of their soul and not on how long they've trudged around like a dip-shit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron laughs.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But it's true.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: It is.
{DIALOGUE}: No question about that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron continues to let Chris vent.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: The government's the same as my parents.
{DIALOGUE}: They don't respect anybody.
{DIALOGUE}: Regulation.
{DIALOGUE}: Regulation.
{DIALOGUE}: Regulation.
{DIALOGUE}: WE can't do this.
{DIALOGUE}: But THEY can do that.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, the hypocrisy of the whole...culture.
{DIALOGUE}: Makes me crazy.
{DIALOGUE}: My father was having children with two women at the same time, and then has the gall to think that he can be of some guidance to me?
{DIALOGUE}: Make judgments on me?
{DIALOGUE}: My mother, of course, goes along with all of it.
{DIALOGUE}: Keeps the secret, which of course, makes my whole life a fiction.
{DIALOGUE}: Everything I thought was, wasn't.
{DIALOGUE}: They're such fools!
{DIALOGUE}: Fucking idiots!
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 107.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Alex, please don't lump me in amongst your judges.
{DIALOGUE}: And your tyrants.
{DIALOGUE}: But I'd prefer to not hear that kind of language.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (realizing his slip)
{DIALOGUE}: Sorry.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't usually use that kind of language either.
{DIALOGUE}: I just get so angry thinking about it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron reaches across the table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Puts his sturdy hand on Chris' shoulder.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: You got a lot of passion, young man.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris smiles at Ron.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 191 EXT. CHRIS' CAMP BESIDE THE STONE WALL - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ron and Chris pull up in the pick-up truck, we see SPORADIC FIREWORKS WHISTLING AND CRACKLING into the air above the hot-springs, and HEAR the distant HOOTING of its inhabitants.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris hops out and walks around to Ron's side of the truck.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Awww, that was a great time Mr. Franz.
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Look here.
{DIALOGUE}: If Charles Manson and his buddies don't kill me on my way out of here, I'd like to cook you up a home cooked meal tomorrow night.
{DIALOGUE}: If I come out here about, say, four o'clock tomorrow, how would that be?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: That would be swell.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron is thrilled.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Good, good.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm no gourmet but I know where the spices are.
{DIALOGUE}: Good night, kid.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Good night Mr. Franz.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 108.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And with that, Ron hits the road.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 192 EXT. STONE WALL - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris hikes up it with his backpack on, one laborious step at a time.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 193 EXT. STONE WALL SUMMIT - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris summiting the rock formation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks down over the desert and there before him, The Salton Sea.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 194 EXT. RON'S HOUSE, SALTON SEA - SUNSET
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The house is a single-level, beige structure, sitting between the Salton Sea and a small inlet where he keeps a fishing boat.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Underneath a canopy in the backyard, there is a small workshop of some kind.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: HIGH ANGLE: Chris, looking at his own reflection in the water below Ron's dock.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the reflection, we see his hands full of dirty laundry.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 195 INT. KITCHEN, RON'S HOUSE - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron broils a couple of steaks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris enters and moves past Ron carrying his laundry into another room.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 196 INT. LAUNDRY ROOM, RON'S HOUSE - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pours detergent over his long-in-need clothes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Starts the cycle.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 197 INT. KITCHEN, RON'S HOUSE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Chris enters, Ron is pulling the steaks from the broiler.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 109.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Above the kitchen sink, Chris sees a row of approximately ten photographs, each in vertical 4x6 frames, some black and white, some color: all of Japanese boys and girls in formal American and Japanese attire.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Did you find everything you need?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (breaking his gaze from the photographs)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{DIALOGUE}: I hope I don't wreck your machine.
{DIALOGUE}: There's a lot of grime in that stuff.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Well, that's what it's for.
{DIALOGUE}: How do these steaks look?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron pops the steaks on the kitchen table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Great.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Well, sit down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron grabs some silverware from a drawer, plops it down on the kitchen table with some paper napkins.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: What do you drink?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You got a White Russian?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Nope.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Beer?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Nope.
{DIALOGUE}: Don't have any alcohol.
{DIALOGUE}: I had to quit all that.
{DIALOGUE}: How about a guava juice?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll take a guava juice, that sounds good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ron gets the drinks -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I had a little spell with the bottle, you could say.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 110.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron pops the drinks down on the table, then sits with Chris.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They lift their glasses toward one another, then -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON/CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Cheers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I spent most of my life in the army.
{DIALOGUE}: On New Year's Eve 1957, I was stationed over in Okinawa.
{DIALOGUE}: My wife and son were here in the States, just driving down the road when a fellow who'd had too much to drink plowed right into them.
{DIALOGUE}: Killed them both.
{DIALOGUE}: Anyway, you might think that the last thing in the world I'd do, is go to the whiskey, but at the time, it felt like the only thing I could do.
{DIALOGUE}: And I did it hard.
{DIALOGUE}: But pretty soon, I figured I wasn't doing my wife and son any good, mourning them with a bottle.
{DIALOGUE}: So, I pulled myself together and quit drinking, cold turkey.
{DIALOGUE}: And then...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron, spinning his body around, points to the photographs over the sink.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (brightening)
{DIALOGUE}: You see all these kids over here?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I was gonna ask you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, that's...
{META_DATA}: (pointing at each with his finger)
{DIALOGUE}: Fuki, Kenjiro, Yoshiko, Keiko, Masaro, Junichi, Kimpei, Nayoko...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: For the last picture frame, Ron stands and takes it off the shelf -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (pridefully shows Chris the picture)
{DIALOGUE}: And this is Akira.
{DIALOGUE}: Just finished medical school.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris takes the picture and studies Akira's face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron sits back down.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 111.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, I unofficially adopted all of them.
{DIALOGUE}: It did my heart some good but I guess really it was just writing a few letters and sending some money.
{DIALOGUE}: Anyway, it was important to me.
{DIALOGUE}: I get a letter from each of them from time to time.
{DIALOGUE}: You know.
{DIALOGUE}: So, since all that, this is pretty much me.
{META_DATA}: (indicating his small reclusive abode)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Do you ever travel, Mr. Franz?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: No.
{DIALOGUE}: I can't seem to get too far from my leather.
{DIALOGUE}: I'll show you after you finish eating.
{DIALOGUE}: I do a lot of leather engraving.
{DIALOGUE}: I got a little workshop in the garage.
{DIALOGUE}: Between that and my pension, I do pretty well.
{DIALOGUE}: But every time I think I might take a trip somewhere, I get too far behind on orders and such to consider it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (having wolfed down the steak)
{DIALOGUE}: Well, I'm finished eating.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd love to see your workshop.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Would ya?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris nods.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (standing)
{DIALOGUE}: Alright then.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron picks up the picture of Akira and replaces it on the shelf above the sink.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 198 INT. RON'S GARAGE/WORKSHOP - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As we begin, Ron is instructing Chris in the skills of leather engraving.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 112.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 199 EXT. CHRIS' CAMP BESIDE THE STONE WALL - MORNING
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris, a clear plastic bag of clean laundry beside him, sits alone, cross-legged.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He begins to carve into a leather belt.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 200 EXT. STONE WALL - LATER
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow Chris in a LOW ANGLE up his mountain run framing from mid-back to just above his head, sweating profusely.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 201 EXT. 4X4 TRACK, ANZA-BORREGO DESERT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron's truck cuts along the 4x4 track.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BACK TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 202 EXT. STONE WALL, ANZA-BORREGO DESERT - SAME
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris reaching the summit.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He bends over to catch his breath, hands on knees.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (O.S)
{DIALOGUE}: How about some fishing?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris turns to the voice.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And down at the bottom of the rock wall beside the campsite, is Ron holding up two fishing poles.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (referring to the Sea)
{DIALOGUE}: That thing's twice as salty as the ocean.
{DIALOGUE}: Did you know that?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris has barely the breath to speak.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Anything alive in it?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron shrugs his shoulders in a "who cares?"
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: fashion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris laughs but nods in the affirmative and gives Ron the thumbs up.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 113.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 203 EXT. ANZA-BARREGO DESERT - DAY + NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: BEGIN MUSIC OVER: MONTAGE:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 1.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris and Ron fishing in the Salton Sea.
{META_DATA}: (no catch)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At Ron's workshop/garage, Ron guides Chris in his leather belt project.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At Chris' campsite, Chris does push-ups while Ron sits on the tailgate of his truck spying on the "Manson family" through binoculars, shaking his head.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 4.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris at his campsite working on the belt by campfire light.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We MOVE IN on the belt, he's beginning to form the letter N in the leather.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 5.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris jogging in the morning beside Oh-My-God Hot Springs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 6.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris and Ron at the leather bench in Ron's workshop/garage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In a EXTREME CLOSE-UP, MUSIC FADES OUT as we PAN across Chris' leather belt and the story being told on it through the engravings:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 204 EXT. RON'S WORKSHOP - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ALEX is inscribed at the belt's left end; then the initials C.J.M. (for Christopher Johnson McCandless) frame a skull and crossbones.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Across the strip of cowhide one sees a rendering of two-lane blacktop, a No U- turn sign, a thunderstorm producing a flash flood that engulfs a car, a hitchhiker's thumb, an eagle, the Sierra Nevada, salmon cavorting in the Pacific Ocean, the Pacific Coast Highway from Oregon to Washington, the Rocky Mountains, Montana wheat fields, a South Dakota rattlesnake, Westerberg's house in Carthage, the Colorado River rapids, a canoe beached beside a tent, Las Vegas, and at the buckle end, finally, the letter N.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: What's the N stand for?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: ...North.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 114.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 205 EXT. CHRIS' CAMP BESIDE THE STONE WALL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: AN ISOLATED CLOUD ECLIPSES THE SUN AGAINST A BLUE DESERT SKY.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron is sitting on his tailgate, watching Chris, backpack on, climb the stone wall.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Alaska?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris summits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Son, what the hell you running from?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{META_DATA}: (yells down from above)
{DIALOGUE}: I could ask you the same question.
{DIALOGUE}: Except I already know the answer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: You do, do you?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I do, Mr. Franz.
{DIALOGUE}: You've got to get back out in the world.
{DIALOGUE}: Get out of that lonely house of yours, that little workshop, and go live on the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron waves him off.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Really.
{DIALOGUE}: You're going to live a long time, Ron.
{DIALOGUE}: You should make a radical change in your lifestyle.
{DIALOGUE}: The core of man's spirit comes with new experiences.
{DIALOGUE}: And there you are, stubborn old man, sitting on your butt.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Sittin' on my butt, huh?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron gets up off the tailgate.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll show you sittin' on my butt.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And Ron starts making the old man hustle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Shifty shoulders and all, up the stone wall.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 115.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (mumbling)
{DIALOGUE}: "Stubborn old man."
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is laughing and clapping.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Come on, old man!
{DIALOGUE}: Come on!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{META_DATA}: (mumbling)
{DIALOGUE}: Ya little pinhead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris is jumping up and down, thrilled for Ron's efforts.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Now the old man's shuffle has turned into an old man's walk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: But he ain't stopping.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: And bit by bit he shows he's got it in him after all.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ron is just about to mount the summit, Chris extends a hand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron swats it away.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Ya little pinhead.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron drops down onto his back to catch his breath and let his thumping heart slow down.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: You alright?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron, after taking one more deep breath, sits up and Chris sits next to him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's actually pretty happy with himself.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He looks out and sees the distant Salton Sea.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to miss you when you go.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: I'll miss you too, Ron.
{DIALOGUE}: But you're wrong if you think the joy of life comes principally from human relationships.
{DIALOGUE}: God's placed it all around us.
{DIALOGUE}: It's in everything.
{DIALOGUE}: In anything we can experience.
{DIALOGUE}: People just have to change the way they think about those things.
{DIALOGUE}: You ought to put a little camper on the back of your pick-up and go take a look at some of the great work god's done out here in the American west.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Alex..
{DIALOGUE}: You're probably right.
{DIALOGUE}: And I'm going to take stock of that.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 116.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris offers a skeptical glance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: No, I am.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A second skeptical glance.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Which Ron squashes with genuine sincerity.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{META_DATA}: (almost to himself)
{DIALOGUE}: I am.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris buys it this time and feels he's accomplished something with Ron.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: But I'll tell you something.
{DIALOGUE}: The bits and pieces I've put together, you know, what you've told me about your family.
{DIALOGUE}: Your mother and dad.
{DIALOGUE}: And I know you got your problems with the church too, but there's some kind of bigger thing that we can all appreciate.
{DIALOGUE}: And it sounds like you don't mind calling it God.
{DIALOGUE}: But when you forgive, you love.
{DIALOGUE}: And when you love...God's light shines on you.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Miraculously, it is just at that moment that the cloud clears from the sun and the light shines in Ron's eyes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris points at Ron's face at the light shining on him -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Holy Shit!
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I told you about that language.
{DIALOGUE}: The two men, their eyes welling up, fall back laughing.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: EXTREME WIDE SHOT FROM BELOW: The two men on the summit with the echoing of laughter and Ron's screams -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I told you so!
{DIALOGUE}: I told you so!
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 206 INT. LAUNDRY ROOM, RON'S HOUSE - NIGHT (MARCH 11, 1992)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris pulls his laundry out of the dryer.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He's got his pack sitting in the doorway to the kitchen.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He folds his things and tucks them into his pack.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 117.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron appears in the doorway dressed for travel.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: What are you doing up?
{DIALOGUE}: It's three-thirty in the morning.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Heard you get up off the couch half an hour ago, and had a funny feeling you might not be here for our breakfast.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris says nothing.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I'm going to drive you a hundred miles to somewhere where you can pick up a train, a plane, or hitch a ride without getting stuck on this desert.
{DIALOGUE}: I'd take you all the way to Alaska if I didn't have to get to an eight o'clock mass.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Ron, you don't have to do that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I want to do it.
{DIALOGUE}: Get you started on this thing of yours.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: On my Great -
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{META_DATA}: (interrupting)
{DIALOGUE}: I know.
{DIALOGUE}: On your "Great Alaskan Adventure."
{DIALOGUE}: From just out of Chris' eye-line, Ron leans out of frame, picking up a zippered duffel bag.
{DIALOGUE}: He opens it, displaying the contents to Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: There's a machete, an arctic parka, collapsible fishing pole, and a few odds and ends I threw in there for you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Ron...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Oh, just take it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris does, nodding his thanks.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 118.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: I'll wait for you in the truck.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 207 EXT. HIGHWAY 10, OUTSIDE SALTON CITY - DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We follow the two men (on this nondescript locale) driving along the highway east from dawn through sunrise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They ride in silence through Coachchella Desert Center and Blythe.
{META_DATA}: CUT TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 208 EXT. HIGHWAY 10
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The truck exits at a North/South junction 95.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 209 INT. RON'S TRUCK
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As Ron begins to pull over.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: Well my friend.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Yep.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Both of them are uncomfortable.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris goes for the door handle.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron's gnarled hand reaches out to take Chris' elbow.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: After a long beat, Ron speaks without looking at Chris.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{DIALOGUE}: I had an idea.
{DIALOGUE}: You know my mother was an only child.
{DIALOGUE}: So was my father.
{DIALOGUE}: And I was their only child.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, with my own boy gone, I'm the end of the line.
{DIALOGUE}: When I'm gone, my family will be finished.
{DIALOGUE}: What do you say, you let me adopt you.
{DIALOGUE}: I could be, say, your grandfather.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This takes Chris by surprise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He knew it would be hard but not this hard.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: How about we talk about this when I get back from Alaska, Ron.
{DIALOGUE}: Would that be alright?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 119.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Silence.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Releases Chris' elbow.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS (CONT'D)
{DIALOGUE}: Alright, Ron.
{DIALOGUE}: We'll talk about it then.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: RON
{META_DATA}: (trying to mask. The blinking, moist eyes again)
{DIALOGUE}: Yep.
{DIALOGUE}: We can do that, yep.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: CHRIS
{DIALOGUE}: Thanks, Ron.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron nods.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris gets out of the truck.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ron watches as Chris saddles up his bag including the duffel that Ron gave him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Chris crosses the exit junction to where he can pick up a ride north on the far side of the road.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We ZOOM SLOWLY through the windshield into Ron's face as he watches Chris hitching away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We HEAR the first bars of Neil Young's My My, Hey Hey.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: This will carry throughout the following MONTAGE.
{META_DATA}: DISSOLVE TO:
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: 210 INT./EXT. VARIOUS - MONTAGE
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 1.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We ZOOM into Walt McCandless' face as he looks through the Questar telescope that Chris had given him.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ANGLE: The stars through the telescope.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The same stars his son walks under...somewhere.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PAN ACROSS SPACE.
{META_DATA}: (Note: This montage will intercut Chris' traveling POV with objective shots. However, we never SEE Chris.)
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 2.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We PULL BACK from the starry night sky to see it framed from within a moving train.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 3.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Carine in her shower, water cascades over her face.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 4.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Billie in her kitchen, making dinner.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 5.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Through the windshield of a semi-truck, the sun rises on Glacier National Park.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 6.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A HANDHELD ZOOM-OUT from Canadian border crossing, CAMERA TURNS to the woods beyond and MOVES INTO THEM.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 120.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 7.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SERIES OF TRAVELING SHOTS: (Through Skookumchuk and Radium Junction, Lake Louise to Prince George and Dawson Creek) STATIC NATURE SHOTS: HELICOPTER SHOTS
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 8.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On the bed in their van, Jan sits on Rainey's bare feet while he does sit-ups.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: 9.
